er|title= Remarks Remade: The Story of R.E.M.|publisher= Omnibus|date= 2002|isbn= 0-7119-9113-8}}</ref>|accessdate=November 11, 2019}}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=yes}}\n\n==Notes and sources==\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n*Black, Johnny. ''Reveal: The Story of R.E.M.'' Backbeat, 2004. {{ISBN|0-87930-776-5}}\n*Buckley, David. ''R.E.M.: Fiction: An Alternative Biography''. Virgin, 2002. {{ISBN|1-85227-927-3}}\n*Platt, John (editor). ''The R.E.M. Companion: Two Decades of Commentary''. Schirmer, 1998. {{ISBN|0-02-864935-4}}\n\n==Citations==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{R.E.M.}}\n\n[[Category:1994 albums]]\n[[Category:R.E.M. albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Bill Berry]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Michael Stipe]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Mike Mills]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Peter Buck]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Scott Litt]]\n[[Category:Warner Records albums]]\n[[Category:Hard rock albums by American artists]]\n[[Category:Punk rock albums by American artists]]\n[[Category:Grunge albums]]\n[[Category:Glam rock albums by American artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Monster\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[R.E.M.]]\n| cover      = R.E.M. - Monster.jpg\n| alt        = An album cover showing a blurred drawing of a bear's head in black against an orange background. The name of the album is in red text in the top-left corner of the cover and the band's name is in blue text on a black background in the top-right corner of the cover.\n| released   = {{Start date|1994|09|27|mf=yes}}\n| recorded   = October 1993&nbsp;\u2013 May 1994\n| studio     = {{ubl|Kingsway Studio, New Orleans|Crossover Soundstage, Atlanta|[[Criteria Studios]], Miami|[[Ocean Way Recording]], Los Angeles}}\n| genre      =\n*[[Grunge]]\n*[[alternative rock]]\n*{{nowrap|[[punk rock]]}}\n*[[glam rock]]\n| length     = 49:15\n| label      = [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n| producer   =\n*[[Scott Litt]]\n*R.E.M.\n| prev_title = [[The Automatic Box]]\n| prev_year  = 1993\n| next_title = [[R.E.M.: Singles Collected]]\n| next_year  = 1994\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Monster\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[What's the Frequency, Kenneth?]]\n | single1date = September 5, 1994\n | single2     = [[Bang and Blame]]\n | single2date = October 31, 1994\n | single3     = [[Strange Currencies]]\n | single3date = April 18, 1995\n | single4     = [[Crush with Eyeliner]]\n | single4date = August 15, 1995\n | single5     = [[Tongue (song)|Tongue]]\n | single5date = October 31, 1995\n}}\n{{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover\n | type    = studio\n | cover   = Monster 25th Anniversary.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = 25th anniversary edition cover\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Monster''''' is the ninth studio album by American [[rock music|rock]] band [[R.E.M.]], released on September 27, 1994 by [[Warner Bros. Records]]. Produced by the band and [[Scott Litt]] and recorded at four studios, the album was an intentional stylistic shift from R.E.M.'s previous two albums ''[[Out of Time (album)|Out of Time]]'' (1991) and ''[[Automatic for the People]]'' (1992), with loud, distorted guitar tones and simple arrangements. [[Michael Stipe]]'s lyrics at times deal with the nature of celebrity, and some are sung from the viewpoint of a character.\n\nLed by the successful single \"[[What's the Frequency, Kenneth?]]\", ''Monster'' debuted at number one in the United States and at least seven other countries, and received generally positive reviews. Four more singles were released from the album, including the UK top-20 hits \"[[Bang and Blame]]\", \"[[Strange Currencies]]\", and \"[[Tongue (song)|Tongue]]\". That year, the band promoted the album with their first concert tour since 1989; although the tour was commercially successful, band members suffered several health problems. The album's follow-up ''[[New Adventures in Hi-Fi]]'' (1996) was primarily recorded during the tour.\n\n==Recording==\nEarly in 1993, R.E.M. convened a four-day meeting in [[Acapulco]] to plan their next two years. The group agreed on a plan for 1994 through 1996, which included recording a new album and touring to promote it.<ref name=\"cavanagh\">Cavanagh, David. \"Tune In, Cheer Up, Rock Out\". ''Q''. October 1994.</ref> Drummer [[Bill Berry]] was particularly eager to tour (which the band had not done since 1989), and insisted that the album \"rock\". The band agreed that after ''[[Out of Time (album)|Out of Time]]'' and ''[[Automatic for the People]]'', they did not want to record another slow-paced album.<ref name=\"buckley236\">Buckley, p. 236</ref>\n\nLater that year, R.E.M. began recording their ninth album.<ref name=\"buckley236\" /> Pre-production took place at Kingsway Studio in [[New Orleans]] under the supervision of Mark Howard, who had worked on ''Automatic for the People''.<ref name=\"Buckley, p. 237\">Buckley, p. 237</ref> Guitarist [[Peter Buck]] said that the band wrote 45 songs, including \"a whole album's worth of acoustic stuff\" which they demoed.<ref name=\"cavanagh\" /> According to Howard, the sessions were experimental: \"The bass had a tremolo sound on it. It was a more inventive session for them.\" The studio did not have a control room, so Howard recorded Michael Stipe singing lyrical ideas while lying on a couch: \"Being able to put those vocals down helped him write the lyrics to a lot of songs on ''Monster''.\"<ref name=\"buckley238\">Buckley, p. 238</ref> When the sessions were finished Howard played the recordings to co-producer Scott Litt, who had worked with the band since their fifth album (''[[Document (album)|Document]]'', 1987).<ref name=\"Buckley, p. 237\"/>\n\n[[File:North Miami FL Criteria Studios01.jpg|thumb|left|alt=White building with a hedge and palm trees in front|Part of ''Monster'' was recorded at [[Criteria Studios]].]]\nIn February 1994, the band moved to Crossover Soundstage in [[Atlanta, Georgia]]. At Crossover, most of the album's basic tracks were recorded live as if the band were playing in concert. Litt said, \"I thought since they hadn't toured in a while, it would be good for them to get into that mind-set\u2014you know, monitors, PA, standing up\".<ref name=\"monster madness\">DeCurtis, Anthony. {{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/monster-madness-19941020|title=\"Monster Madness\" |accessdate=August 30, 2016}}. ''Rolling Stone''. October 20, 1994. Retrieved on May 6, 2010.</ref> The sessions were hampered by several events, including Berry and bassist [[Mike Mills]] falling ill on separate occasions, Buck and Stipe leaving to visit family members and the deaths of Stipe's friends, actor [[River Phoenix]] and [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] lead singer [[Kurt Cobain]].<ref name=\"buckley238\" /> The band wrote and recorded \"Let Me In\" in tribute to Cobain and dedicated the album to Phoenix,<ref name=\"monster madness\" /> whose sister [[Rain Phoenix|Rain]] provided background vocals on \"[[Bang and Blame]]\".\n\nIn late April 1994 the band relocated to [[Criteria Studios]] in [[Miami, Florida]], but recording was interrupted because Stipe had an abscessed tooth.<ref>Black, p. 204</ref> Unlike previous album sessions, by the time production moved to [[Ocean Way Recording]] in [[Los Angeles]] the band was behind schedule. Litt attributed the delay to recording live at Crossover, which lengthened the mixing process; he told ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', \"We're trying to figure out how raw to leave it and how much to studiofy it.\" Stipe was still writing songs when the band was supposed to be mixing the album. Tensions arose among the band members, who were staying in different locations in Los Angeles and would rarely be in the studio at the same time.<ref name=\"monster madness\" /> The situation came to a head when the group was recording at Louie's Clubhouse (Litt's home studio in Los Angeles); years later, Stipe recalled, \"We broke up ... We reached the point where none of us could speak to each other, and we were in a small room, and we just said 'Fuck off' and that was it.\"<ref>Black, p. 205</ref> The group met to resolve their issues; Mills told ''Rolling Stone'', \"We have to begin working as a unit again, which we haven't been doing very well lately.\"<ref name=\"monster madness\" />\n\n==Composition==\n{{listen|filename=R.E.M. - What's the Frequency, Kenneth?.ogg|title=\"What's the Frequency, Kenneth?\" |description=Sample of \"What's the Frequency, Kenneth?\", the first single from ''Monster''. The song's loud, distorted guitars were an intentional departure from R.E.M.'s previous two albums.}}\n\nUnlike R.E.M.'s previous two albums, ''Monster'' incorporated distorted guitar tones, minimal overdubs, and touches of 1970s [[glam rock]]. Peter Buck described the album as \"a 'rock' record, with the 'rock' in quotation marks.\" He explained, \"That's not what we started out to make, but that's certainly how it turned out to be. There's a [[Nudge Nudge|nudge, nudge, wink, wink]] feel to the whole record. Like, it's a rock record, but is it really?\"<ref name=\"buckley236\" /> Mike Mills told ''[[Time magazine|Time]]'', \"On past albums we had been exploring acoustic instruments, trying to use the piano and mandolin, and we did it about all we wanted to do it. And you come back to the fact that playing loud electric-guitar music is about as fun as music can be.\"<ref>Farley, Christopher John. \"[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,981499,00.html Monster Music R.E.M., One Of]\". ''Time''. September 26, 1994. Retrieved on August 1, 2008.</ref> Stipe's vocals were pushed down in the mix.<ref name=\"buckley236\" /> Buck's guitar work on the album was inspired by the [[tremolo]]-heavy guitar playing of Glen Johansson of [[Echobelly]], who supported R.E.M. on some of the Monster Tour.<ref>{{cite web|author=John Everhart |url=http://www.stereogum.com/1676549/caught-by-the-buzz-a-look-back-at-britpops-b-list/franchises/20-years-of-britpop/ |title=Caught By The Buzz: A Look Back At Britpop's B-List |website=Stereogum |date=2014-04-23 |accessdate=2016-11-13}}</ref> The album's music has been described as [[grunge]]<ref name=stereogum-bracy>{{cite web|author=Timothy and Elizabeth Bracy |url=http://www.stereogum.com/1099212/r-e-m-albums-from-worst-to-best/photo/attachment/081227394929/ |title=Stereogum |website=Stereogum |date=2012-07-20 |accessdate=2016-11-13}}</ref><ref name=popmusic-encyclopedia>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC&pg=RA1-PA2266&lpg=RA1-PA2266&dq=What%27s+the+Frequency,+Kenneth?+-+grunge&source=bl&ots=JbpSyqZaWs&sig=zaRx3jCw-SuXfwnOHga5stQsDJA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiztqHD5_rKAhUT5GMKHaFFCsE4ChDoAQg5MAk |title=The Encyclopedia of Popular Music |author=Colin Larkin |page=2266 |website=Books.google.com |date=2011-05-27 |accessdate=2016-11-13}}</ref><ref name=\"punkrock\">{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Stewart|title=Sex & Trash Aesthetics: REM's Monster Revisited|url=http://thequietus.com/articles/16426-rem-monster-review-anniversary|website=[[The Quietus]]|accessdate=November 26, 2017|date=October 8, 2014}}</ref> and [[alternative rock]]<ref name=stereogum-leas>{{cite web|last1=Leas|first1=Ryan|title=Monster Turns 20|url=https://www.stereogum.com/1707675/monster-turns-20/franchises/the-anniversary/|website=[[Stereogum]]|accessdate=November 26, 2017|date=September 26, 2014|quote=While it might draw on '70s glam and some of R.E.M.'s own tendencies, Monster is an early '90s alt-rock record through and through.}}</ref><ref name=\"alt-rock\">{{cite web|last1=Schumer|first1=Ben|title=It Starts with an Earthquake: R.E.M.'s Monster|url=https://www.popmatters.com/66852-it-starts-with-an-earthquake-rems-monster-2496094248.html|website=[[PopMatters]]|accessdate=November 26, 2017|date=February 26, 2009}}</ref> by critics. The band has called it a \"foxy, in-your-face, [[punk rock]], trashed and stupid\" record.<ref name=\"punkrock\" /> \"[[What's the Frequency, Kenneth?]]\", \"[[Crush with Eyeliner]]\" and \"Circus Envy\" have been described as glam rock.<ref name=\"punkrock\" />\n\nStipe wrote ''Monster''{{'s}} lyrics in character; this, according to biographer Dan Buckley, \"set the real Stipe at a distance from the mask adopted for each song.\" The album dealt with the nature of celebrity and \"the creepiness of fandom as pathology\".<ref>Buckley, p. 241</ref> Buck called the album a reaction to the band's popularity: \"When I read the lyrics I thought, all these guys are totally fucked up. I don't know who they are, because they're not Michael. I would say that this was the only time where he's done characters that are creepy, and I don't know if anyone got that. He was getting out his things by acting out these parts that are not him.\"<ref>Buckley, p. 243-44</ref> The band noted that at the end of certain songs, they left blank choruses (where Mills and Berry would usually sing harmony) so fans could sing along.<ref name=\"cavanagh\" />\n\n\"The song 'Let Me In' is me on the phone to [[Kurt Cobain|Kurt]], trying to get him out of the frame of mind he was in,\" said Stipe. \"I wanted him to know he didn't need to pay attention to all this; that he was going to make it through. I know what the next [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] record was going to sound like. It was going to be an amazing fucking record, and I'm a little angry at him for [[Death of Kurt Cobain|killing himself]]. He and I were going to make a trial run of the album. It was set up. He had a plane ticket. At the last minute he called and said, 'I can't come.{{'\"}}<ref>quoted in ''[[Select (magazine)|Select]]'', issue date unknown; original source unknown</ref>\n\n==Packaging==\nThe [[cover art]] features a blurred drawing of a bear's head against an orange background. The concept originated when Stipe showed cover artist Chris Bilheimer a balloon he wanted to use as the [[album cover]] and told him to \"play around with\". Bilheimer changed the color of the balloon (which was originally green), and re-photographed the bear head. When he was down to the last few frames on a roll of film, he took a few photos without bothering to focus the shots (which he and Stipe ended up liking the best).<ref>Buckley, p. 247</ref> The jewel case of the original CD release of ''Monster'' also featured an orange polystyrene media tray, akin to the yellow one used for the ''[[Automatic for the People]]'' CD.\n\nThe back cover has the body of the bear next to the track listing, and the inside sleeve features images of the cartoon character [[Migraine Boy]]. \"I lifted Migraine Boy from the ''[[Flagpole Magazine|Flagpole]]'',\" Stipe told Molly McCommons, his 12-year-old interviewer and daughter of ''Flagpole'' editor Pete McCommons. \"I'd like to officially thank ''Flagpole'' for introducing me to Greg Fiering and Migraine Boy. I haven't met Greg, but I've talked to him a lot on the phone. We were actually in [[San Francisco]] at the same time, but I was working on another project and we had a television visit for about two hours. This is an exclusive. I don't think anybody else knows about Migraine Boy yet.\"<ref>''[[Flagpole Magazine|Flagpole]]'', September 1994</ref>\n\nThe booklet contains several alternate names and working titles of songs recorded for the album. In interviews, the band has described its process of naming albums: they tape a large sheet of paper on the studio wall, and then write down random ideas as they occur. One song mentioned on the list is \"Revolution\", an outtake which later appeared on the ''[[Batman & Robin (film)|Batman & Robin]]'' soundtrack and the bonus disc of ''[[In Time: The Best of R.E.M. 1988\u20132003]]''. \"Yes, I Am Fucking with You\" was the working title of \"King of Comedy\".<ref name=\"monster madness\" />\n\nThe limited-edition deluxe CD was packaged with a 52-page hardcover book of photographs and artwork (including Migraine Boy), similar to the visual extras in other 1980s and 1990s limited-edition R.E.M. albums (which were usually overseen and directed by Stipe). The ''Monster'' book also included an [[obi strip]] and a different design printed on the disc itself, which fitted into a die-cut, star-shaped opening inside the book's cover.{{Citation needed|date=October 2018}}\n\n==Release and reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 83/100<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/monster-25th-anniversary-deluxe-edition/rem|title=Monster [25th Anniversary Deluxe Edition] by R.E.M.|website=[[Metacritic]]|date=November 1, 2019|accessdate=November 9, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic review\">{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/monster-mw0000119158 |title=''Monster''&nbsp;\u2013 R.E.M. |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=August 1, 2008 |last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n| rev2score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |title=Back Catalogue: R.E.M. |work=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]] |issue=67 |date=March 2008 |page=106}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''\n| rev3score = {{rating|3.5|4}}<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-11-27/entertainment/9411270042_1_star-band-uber |title=R.E.M.'s Best Album Side? Band Members Say It's Not 'Automatic' |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=November 27, 1994 |accessdate=November 10, 2015 |last=Kot |first=Greg |authorlink=Greg Kot}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev4score = B+<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.ew.com/article/1994/09/30/monster |title=''Monster'' |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=September 30, 1994 |accessdate=May 6, 2010 |last=Browne |first=David |authorlink=David Browne (journalist)}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev5score = {{rating|4|4}}<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1994-09-25/entertainment/ca-42591_1_album-roundup |title=Fall Album Roundup: R.E.M. Builds the Perfect Beast |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=September 25, 1994 |accessdate=August 31, 2015 |last=Hilburn |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Hilburn}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6score = 7/10<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews/19980101001046reviews.html |title=REM&nbsp;\u2013 ''Monster'' |work=[[NME]] |date=September 24, 1994 |accessdate=August 31, 2015 |last=Cameron |first=Keith |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000817182353/http://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews/19980101001046reviews.html |archivedate=August 17, 2000}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev7score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |title=R.E.M.: ''Monster'' |work=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |issue=98 |date=November 1994 |page=118}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8score = {{rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"rolling stone rating\">{{cite journal |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/monster-20010502 |title=''Monster'' |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=October 6, 1994 |accessdate=December 5, 2010 |last=Palmer |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Palmer (writer)}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Select (magazine)|Select]]''\n| rev9score = 3/5<ref>{{cite journal |title=Plodzilla |work=[[Select (magazine)|Select]] |issue=53 |date=November 1994 |page=102 |last=Wilkinson |first=Roy}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| rev10score = A\u2212<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv1094-94.php |title=Consumer Guide |work=[[The Village Voice]] |date=October 18, 1994 |accessdate=August 31, 2015 |last=Christgau |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Christgau}}</ref>\n}}\n''Monster'' debuted at number one on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' charts<ref>\"[http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,304062,00.html Monster Smash]\" ''Entertainment Weekly''. October 14, 1994. Retrieved on July 31, 2008</ref> and the British album charts.<ref>Black, p. 207</ref> There were several hits from the album; particularly \"What's the Frequency, Kenneth?\" and \"[[Bang and Blame]]\", which charted better than any single from ''Automatic for the People'' in the United States<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/music/rem/chart-history/hot-100 | title=R.E.M. \u2013 Chart History: Hot 100 | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | accessdate=March 31, 2018}}</ref> and Canada.<ref>{{cite journal | url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.2655&type=1&interval=36&PHPSESSID=c6btf3r8hs459qqt5ln3o3dcv5 | title=RPM 100 Singles | work=RPM | volume=60 | issue=17 | date=November 14, 1994 | accessdate=December 30, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105100306/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.2655&type=1&interval=36&PHPSESSID=c6btf3r8hs459qqt5ln3o3dcv5 | archive-date=November 5, 2012 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.8002&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=c6btf3r8hs459qqt5ln3o3dcv5 | title=RPM 100 Singles | work=RPM | volume=61 | issue=3 | date=February 20, 1995 | accessdate=December 30, 2012 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107190643/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.8002&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=c6btf3r8hs459qqt5ln3o3dcv5 | archivedate=November 7, 2012}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|Excluding \"[[Everybody Hurts]]\" from ''Automatic for the People'', this also included the national charts in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=R.E.M. |title=Discography R.E.M. |publisher=Hung Medien |work=australian-charts.com |accessdate=December 26, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905040949/http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=R.E.M. |archivedate=September 5, 2015}}</ref>|group=\"nb\"}} These two singles were also successful in the United Kingdom, peaking at number nine and number 15 respectively.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/18727/r-e-m-/ | title=R.E.M. | publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] | accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref> \"[[Star 69 (R.E.M. song)|Star 69]]\" also charted, although it was not released as a single. The album was among the first promoted with online content, which was also distributed via [[floppy disk]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2018}}\n\nThe album was generally praised; ''Rolling Stone'' gave ''Monster'' four-and-a-half stars.<ref name=\"rolling stone rating\" /> Critic [[Robert Palmer (writer)|Robert Palmer]] noted that Stipe's lyrics dealt with issues of identity (\"The concept of reality itself is being called into question: Is this my life or an incredible virtual simulation?\"), and the singer occasionally \"begins to sound not unlike the proverbial rock star, whining about all those fans who just won't let him alone.\" Palmer added, \"What's truly impressive about ''Monster'' is the way R.E.M. make an album with such potentially grave subject matter so much fun.\"<ref name=\"rolling stone rating\" /> ''[[NME]]'' gave the album a seven-out-of-ten rating. Reviewer Keith Cameron wrote, \"It's fun, frequently, but we feel distanced, engaged only on a secondhand level. Moreover, the loudly trumpeted fox factor has been conspicuous by its absence.\" According to Cameron, \"At best stunning, at worst merely diverting, ''Monster'' sounds like the album they 'had' to make, to clear out their system, a simple prop to occupy our time ...\"<ref>Cameron, Keith. ''Monster'' review. ''NME''. September 24, 1994.</ref> Allmusic gave the album two-and-a-half stars out of five; [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] wrote, \"''Monster'' doesn't have the conceptual unity or consistently brilliant songwriting of ''Automatic for the People'', but it does offer a wide range of sonic textures that have never been heard on an R.E.M. album before.\"<ref name=\"allmusic review\" />\nIt was voted number 786 in the third edition of [[Colin Larkin]]'s ''[[All Time Top 1000 Albums]]'' (2000).<ref name=\"Larkin\">{{cite book|title=[[All Time Top 1000 Albums]]|editor=[[Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Virgin Books]]|date=2000|edition=3rd|isbn=0-7535-0493-6|page=247}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Warner Bros. released expanded two-disc editions of all the band's Warner Bros. studio albums. The ''Monster'' reissue included a CD, a [[DVD-Audio]] disc with a 5.1-channel surround-sound mix of the album, and concert footage from the Monster Tour.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sweeting |first1=Adam |title=REM, Monster |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/feb/04/popandrock.shopping24 |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=June 24, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180527091545/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/feb/04/popandrock.shopping24 |archivedate=May 27, 2018 |date=February 3, 2005}}</ref> The original CD booklet's liner notes were expanded with lyrics and a photo gallery.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/release/monster-cd-dvd-audio-mr0001135042 |title=''Monster'' [CD & DVD Audio]&nbsp;\u2013 R.E.M. |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=August 1, 2008 |last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011 ''Monster'' was ranked ninth on ''[[Guitar World]]''{{'s}} top-ten list of 1994 guitar albums, between [[Rancid (band)|Rancid]]'s ''[[Let's Go (Rancid album)|Let's Go]]'' and [[Tesla (band)|Tesla]]'s ''[[Bust a Nut]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.guitarworld.com/readers-poll-results-top-10-guitar-albums-1994 |title=Photo Gallery: The Top 10 Guitar Albums of 1994 |author=Grassi, Tony |magazine=[[Guitar World|GuitarWorld.com]] |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> ''Guitar World'' also included the album on their \"Superunknown: 50 Iconic Albums That Defined 1994\" list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guitarworld.com/superunknown-50-iconic-albums-defined-1994 |title=Superunknown: 50 Iconic Albums That Defined 1994 |date=July 14, 2014 |work=[[Guitar World|GuitarWorld.com]] |accessdate=July 14, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715053900/http://www.guitarworld.com/superunknown-50-iconic-albums-defined-1994 |archivedate=July 15, 2014 }}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' originally named it the year's second-best album, but dropped it to fifteenth-best in a 2014 re-ranking.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/Current/A907.htm |title=Monster |publisher=Acclaimed Music |date= |accessdate=2016-11-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819135643/http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/Current/A907.htm |archive-date=2016-08-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \"What's the Frequency, Kenneth?\" was ranked at number 16 of ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''{{'}}s list of The 20 Best R.E.M. Songs of All Time in 2009,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jackson |first1=Josh |title=The 20 Best R.E.M. Songs of All Time |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/lists/2009/07/the-20-best-rem-songs-of-all-time.html |website=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |accessdate=July 10, 2018 |date=July 28, 2009}}</ref> number 11 of ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''{{'}}s list of R.E.M.\u2019s Top 20 Songs,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Roffman |first1=Michael |title=R.E.M.\u2019s Top 20 Songs |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/11/r-e-m-s-top-20-songs/2/ |website=[[Consequence of Sound]] |accessdate=July 10, 2018 |date=November 8, 2017}}</ref> and number 19 of [[ThoughtCo]]'s list of the Top 40 Best R.E.M. Songs.<ref name=\"thought-best40\">{{cite web |last1=Grierson |first1=Tim |title=Top 40 Best R.E.M. Songs |url=https://www.thoughtco.com/top-best-r-e-m-songs-2897985 |publisher=[[ThoughtCo]] |accessdate=July 10, 2018 |date=November 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Tour==\n[[File:R.E.M. (75).JPG|alt=Mills playing bass guitar and singing|thumb|After not touring for their previous two albums, R.E.M. used an elaborate rock show to promote ''Monster''; bassist Mike Mills ''(pictured in 2008)'' had a new look, with long hair and [[Nudie suit]]s.]]\nDespite their highest chart positions to date in 1991 and 1992, R.E.M. elected not to tour after they found the year-long ''Green'' tour exhausting.<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/rem-mn0000325459/biography |title=R.E.M. &#124; Biography & History |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=2016-11-13}}</ref> The Monster Tour was the group's first outing in six years. The tour, which played arenas and amphitheaters, began in January 1995 with shows in Australia and Japan and continued throughout Europe and the United States for the rest of the year. Support acts included [[Sonic Youth]] and [[Radiohead]]. Although the tour was a commercial success, it was difficult for the group.<ref>Buckley, p. 248</ref> On March 1, Berry collapsed onstage during a performance in [[Lausanne, Switzerland]] due to a [[brain aneurysm]]. He had surgery immediately, and recovered fully within a month. Berry's aneurysm was the beginning of a series of health problems for the band; Mills had surgery to remove an intestinal adhesion in July, and a month later Stipe had emergency surgery to repair a [[hernia]].<ref>Buckley, p. 251\u201355</ref> However, the group composed and debuted a number of new songs on the tour and recorded most of ''[[New Adventures in Hi-Fi]]'' (their next album) on the road. They used eight-track recorders to capture the shows, and based the new album on those recordings.<ref>Buckley, p. 256</ref>\n\n==25th anniversary reissue==\nR.E.M. decided to release a 25th anniversary deluxe edition of ''Monster'' in 2019, after having released such an edition for ''Monster'''s predecessor, ''[[Automatic for the People]]'', in 2017. The edition contains remastered, live and demo versions of the songs from the album, as well as, unusually, a CD containing a fully remixed version of the album. The remix was the brainchild of original producer Scott Litt, who had long regretted the original mixing job he had done on ''Monster'', which involved distortion and vocals low in the mix, in keeping with the [[grunge]] style popular at the time.<ref name=\"revisiting monster\">{{cite web |title=R.E.M. Producer Scott Litt on Revisiting \u2018Monster\u2019 25 Years Later |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/davidchiu/2019/11/06/rem-producer-scott-litt-on-revisiting-monster25-years-later/#7eee25ce23e9 |first=David |last=Chiu |work=Forbes |date=November 6, 2019}}</ref> He felt that the tracks were unnecessarily muddy and did not make for a cohesive album, and noted that, at used record stores, he always saw copies of ''Monster'' that people had given away, and rarely copies of R.E.M.'s other albums, indicating listener dissatisfaction.<ref name=\"revisiting monster\" /> For the 25th anniversary remix, Litt made Stipe's and others' vocals more prominent and clearer, removed some instrumental tracks (like the staccato guitar in the chorus of \"What's the Frequency, Kenneth?\"),<ref>{{cite AV media |title=R.E.M. Monster 25 - Interview with producer, Scott Litt |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=19hhctlleNo |publisher=YouTube |date=September 5, 2019}}</ref> and even used some different vocal takes, for example in \"Strange Currencies\".<ref>{{cite AV media |title=R.E.M. - \"Strange Currencies\" Remix (Interview with Scott Litt) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UHMpF8CZoSQ |publisher=YouTube |date=November 12, 2019}}</ref> He cited the new version of \"Let Me In\", whose vocals are more comprehensible, as \"maybe the best example of what's going on in the remix, which is simplicity\".<ref>{{cite AV media |title=R.E.M. \"Let Me In\" Remix - Interview with Scott Litt |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HbBzQ1PmX70 |publisher=YouTube |date=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe members of R.E.M., while supportive of the remix, said that they were still happy with the original production, saying that, in Stipe's words, it conveyed \"exactly who we were at that moment in time.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=REM look back on Monster: 'We did not want to become the dancing monkey' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-50206491 |first=Mark |last=Savage |work=BBC |date=October 29, 2019}}</ref> The music website [[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] was critical of the remix, writing, \"the inescapable excess of Buck\u2019s guitar tone as well as the slipperiness of Stipe\u2019s vocals are what make the record special; when you invert these effects, it starts to be indistinguishable from any other R.E.M. record.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Monster (25th Anniversary Edition) |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/rem-monster-25th-anniversary-edition/ |first=Brad |last=Nelson |work=Pitchfork |date=November 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs written by [[Bill Berry]], [[Peter Buck]], [[Mike Mills]] and [[Michael Stipe]].\n\n'''Side one&nbsp;\u2013 \"C side\"'''\n#\"[[What's the Frequency, Kenneth?]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:00\n#\"[[Crush with Eyeliner]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:39\n#\"King of Comedy\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:40\n#\"I Don't Sleep, I Dream\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:27\n#\"[[Star 69 (R.E.M. song)|Star 69]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:07\n#\"[[Strange Currencies]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:52\n\n'''Side two&nbsp;\u2013 \"D side\"'''\n#<li value=\"7\">\"[[Tongue (song)|Tongue]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:13</li>\n#\"[[Bang and Blame]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 5:30\n#\"I Took Your Name\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:02\n#\"Let Me In\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:28\n#\"Circus Envy\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:15\n#\"You\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:54\n\n===25th anniversary edition===\nThe 25th anniversary edition includes a remastered album and several bonus discs:\n\n'''Disc 2 (CD) \u2013 ''Monster'' (Demos)'''\n#\"Pete's Hit\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:22\n#\"Uptempo Mo Distortion\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:18\n#\"Uptempo Ricky\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:53\n#\"Harlan County with Whistling\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:04\n#\"Lost Song\"&nbsp;\u2013 5:43\n#\"AM Boo\"&nbsp;\u2013 1:00\n#\"Mike's Gtr\"&nbsp;\u2013 5:05\n#\"Sputnik 1 Remix\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:30\n#\"Black Sky 4-14\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:17\n#\"Revolution 4-21\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:22\n#\"Rocker with Vocal\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:58\n#\"Time Is on Mike's Side\"&nbsp;\u2013 5:02\n#\"Experiment 4-28 No Vocal\"&nbsp;\u2013 5:35\n#\"Highland Fling 4-29\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:54\n#\"Cranky 4-29\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:41\n\n'''Disc 3 (CD) \u2013 ''Monster'' (2019 Scott Litt Remixes)'''\n#\"What's the Frequency, Kenneth?\" (Remix)&nbsp;\u2013 3:39\n#\"Crush with Eyeliner\" (Remix)&nbsp;\u2013 4:35\n#\"King of Comedy\" (Remix)&nbsp;\u2013 4:00\n#\"I Don't Sleep, I Dream\" (Remix)&nbsp;\u2013 3:56\n#\"Star 69\" (Remix)&nbsp;\u2013 3:07\n#\"Strange Currencies\" (Remix)&nbsp;\u2013 3:52\n#<li value=\"7\">\"Tongue\" (Remix)&nbsp;\u2013 4:00</li>\n#\"Bang and Blame\" (Remix)&nbsp;\u2013 5:12\n#\"I Took Your Name\" (Remix)&nbsp;\u2013 4:02\n#\"Let Me In\" (Remix)&nbsp;\u2013 3:08\n#\"Circus Envy\" (Remix)&nbsp;\u2013 4:15\n#\"You\" (Remix)&nbsp;\u2013 4:50\n\n'''Disc 4 (CD) \u2013 Live in Chicago 6/3/95 \u2013 Monster 1995 Tour (Part One)'''\n#\"What's the Frequency, Kenneth?\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:59\n#\"Circus Envy\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:24\n#\"Crush with Eyeliner\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:38\n#\"[[Near Wild Heaven]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:57\n#\"Welcome to the Occupation\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:06\n#\"Undertow\"&nbsp;\u2013 5:19\n#\"I Took Your Name\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:29\n#\"Strange Currencies\"&nbsp;\u2013 5:00\n#\"Me in Honey\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:22\n#\"Revolution\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:56\n#\"Tongue\"&nbsp;\u2013 5:26\n#\"[[Man on the Moon (song)|Man on the Moon]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 5:51\n#\"[[Country Feedback]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 6:03\n#\"Monty Got a Raw Deal\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:21\n\n'''Disc 5 (CD) \u2013 Live in Chicago 6/3/95 \u2013 Monster 1995 Tour (Part Two)'''\n#<li value=\"15\">\"[[Losing My Religion]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:54\n#\"You\"&nbsp;\u2013 5:07\n#\"Departure\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:44\n#\"[[Orange Crush (song)|Orange Crush]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:54\n#\"[[Get Up (R.E.M. song)|Get Up]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 2:55\n#\"Star 69\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:07\n#\"Let Me In\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:42\n#\"[[Everybo