oulomb's Law]\u2014a game created by the Molecular Workbench software\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090314044312/http://ocw.mit.edu/OcwWeb/Physics/8-02Electricity-and-MagnetismSpring2002/VideoAndCaptions/detail/embed01.htm Electric Charges, Polarization, Electric Force, Coulomb's Law] Walter Lewin, ''8.02 Electricity and Magnetism, Spring 2002: Lecture 1'' (video). MIT OpenCourseWare. License: Creative Commons Attribution-Noncommercial-Share Alike.\n\n[[Category:Electrostatics]]\n[[Category:Force]]\n[[Category:Scientific laws]]\n", "name_user": "82.1.76.239", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coulomb%27s_law"}
{"title_page": "Claude Humphrey", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|image=\n|position=[[Defensive end]]\n|number=87\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1944|6|29}}\n|birth_place=[[Memphis, Tennessee]]\n|height_ft=6\n|height_in=4\n|weight_lbs = 252\n|draftyear=1968\n|draftround=1\n|draftpick=3\n|high_school = [[Lester High School|Memphis (TN) Lester]]\n|college=[[Tennessee State Tigers football|Tennessee State]]\n|teams=\n* [[Atlanta Falcons]] ([[1968 NFL season|1968]]\u2013[[1974 NFL season|1974]], [[1976 NFL season|1976]]\u2013[[1978 NFL season|1978]])\n* [[Philadelphia Eagles]] ([[1979 NFL season|1979]]\u2013[[1981 NFL season|1981]])\n|statlabel1=Games\n|statvalue1=171\n|statlabel2=[[Safety (American football score)|Safeties]]\n|statvalue2=2\n|nflnew=claudehumphrey/2517032\n|HOF=claude-humphrey\n|highlights=\n* 6\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[1971 Pro Bowl|1970]]\u2013[[1975 Pro Bowl|1974]], [[1978 Pro Bowl|1977]])\n* 5\u00d7 First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[1971 All-Pro Team|1971]]\u2013[[1974 All-Pro Team|1974]], [[1977 All-Pro Team|1977]])\n* 3\u00d7 Second-team All-Pro ([[1969 All-Pro Team|1969]], [[1970 All-Pro Team|1970]], [[1976 All-Pro Team|1976]])\n* [[NFL Defensive Rookie of the Year]] (1968)\n* [[Atlanta Falcons#Ring of Honor|Falcons Ring of Honor]]\n* First-team [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[1967 College Football All-America Team|1967]])\n}}\n\n'''Claude B. Humphrey''' (born June 29, 1944) is a former [[American football]] [[defensive end]] in the [[National Football League]] (NFL) for the [[Atlanta Falcons]] and [[Philadelphia Eagles]]. Humphrey was inducted into the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] in 2014.\n\n==Professional career==\nHumphrey was [[NFL Draft|drafted]] out of [[Tennessee State University]] in the first round of the [[1968 NFL Draft]] with the third overall choice by the Falcons. Humphrey was an [[1967 College Football All-America Team|All-American]] in 1967.\n\nHumphrey's stellar career included being named First-team All-Pro five times (1971\u201374, and 1977), Second- Team All-Pro three times (1969, 1970, 1976), and All-NFC six times (1970\u201374, 1977).  He was second-team All-NFC in 1976 when Humphrey unofficially recorded a career high 15 quarterback sacks. In addition Humphrey was named to the [[Pro Bowl]] six times over the span of his career (1970\u201374 & 1977).\n\nHumphrey finished out his career with the Philadelphia Eagles from 1979\u201381. In 1980 Humphrey was a designated pass rusher, recording a team high 14\u00bd sacks helping the Eagles become NFC champions and earn a spot in [[Super Bowl XV]]. He finished his career with an unofficial 126\u00bd career sacks with the Falcons and Eagles. He retired in 1981, the season before sacks were recorded as an official NFL statistic.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}\n\nDuring Super Bowl XV, Humphrey was called for roughing the passer against [[Oakland Raiders]] quarterback [[Jim Plunkett]]. Humphrey picked up the penalty flag and fired it back at referee [[Ben Dreith]].\n\nHumphrey is a member of the Georgia Hall of Fame and the Tennessee Hall of Fame. His alma mater (Tennessee State University) retired his number and inducted him into their Hall of Fame. His high school has also retired his jersey and he is a member of his high school Hall of Fame, and is a member of the Atlanta Falcons Ring of Honor.\n\nHumphrey is a member of [[Phi Beta Sigma]].\n\n==Outside Football==\n\nClaude Humphrey also had a guest appearance on [[The Dukes of Hazzard]] episode \"Repo Men\" in which he portrayed Big John, a counterfeiter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlantafalcons.com/news/article-1/QA-with-Hall-of-Fame-DE-Claude-Humphrey/ebb05876-1d04-41af-877d-d807a771fb66|title=Q&A with Hall-of-Fame DE Claude Humphrey|author=|date=|website=atlantafalcons.com}}</ref>\n\n== Pro Football Hall of Fame ==\nHumphrey was a final 15 candidate in 2003, 2005, and 2006.  On August 27, 2008, he was named as one of two senior candidates for the 2009 Hall of Fame election.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.profootballhof.com/enshrinement/story.jsp?story_id=2816 |title=Archived copy |access-date=September 3, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080903085641/http://www.profootballhof.com/enshrinement/story.jsp?story_id=2816 |archive-date=September 3, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  In August 2013, he was named as one of two senior candidates for the 2014 Hall of Fame election.\n\nIn February 2014, Claude Humphrey was elected to the Pro Football Hall of Fame on the senior ballot. During his time in football, Humphrey was a revolutionary pass rushing defensive lineman who paved the way for Reggie White, Bruce Smith, and fellow 2014 NFL HOF inductee Michael Strahan.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n\nOn August 2, 2014, Humphrey was officially inducted at the Enshrinement Ceremony where his bust, sculpted by [[Scott Myers]], was unveiled.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/member.jsp?player_id=245 Biography] as a finalist for the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] in 2006.\n\n{{1968 NFL Draft}}\n{{FalconsFirstPick}}\n{{Atlanta Falcons 1968 draft navbox}}\n{{AP Defensive Rookies of the Year}}\n{{Atlanta Falcons}}\n{{2014 Football HOF}}\n{{Pro Football Hall of Fame members}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Humphrey, Claude}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football defensive ends]]\n[[Category:Atlanta Falcons players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Eagles players]]\n[[Category:Tennessee State Tigers football players]]\n[[Category:National Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:National Football League Defensive Rookie of the Year Award winners]]\n[[Category:NFL Europe (WLAF) coaches]]\n[[Category:Pro Football Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Tennessee]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|image=\n|position=[[Defensive end]]\n|number=87\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1944|6|29}}\n|birth_place=[[Memphis, Tennessee]]\n|height_ft=6\n|height_in=4\n|weight_lbs = 252\n|draftyear=1968\n|draftround=1\n|draftpick=3\n|high_school = [[Lester High School|Memphis (TN) Lester]]\n|college=[[Tennessee State Tigers football|Tennessee State]]\n|teams=\n* [[Atlanta Falcons]] ([[1968 NFL season|1968]]\u2013[[1974 NFL season|1974]], [[1976 NFL season|1976]]\u2013[[1978 NFL season|1978]])\n* [[Philadelphia Eagles]] ([[1979 NFL season|1979]]\u2013[[1981 NFL season|1981]])\n|statlabel1=Games\n|statvalue1=171\n|statlabel2=[[Safety (American football score)|Safeties]]\n|statvalue2=2\n|nflnew=claudehumphrey/2517032\n|HOF=claude-humphrey\n|highlights=\n* 6\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[1971 Pro Bowl|1970]]\u2013[[1975 Pro Bowl|1974]], [[1978 Pro Bowl|1977]])\n* 5\u00d7 First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[1971 All-Pro Team|1971]]\u2013[[1974 All-Pro Team|1974]], [[1977 All-Pro Team|1977]])\n* 3\u00d7 Second-team All-Pro ([[1969 All-Pro Team|1969]], [[1970 All-Pro Team|1970]], [[1976 All-Pro Team|1976]])\n* [[NFL Defensive Rookie of the Year]] (1968)\n* [[Atlanta Falcons#Ring of Honor|Falcons Ring of Honor]]\n* First-team [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[1967 College Football All-America Team|1967]])\n}}\n\n'''Claude B. Humphrey''' (born June 29, 1944) is a former [[American football]] [[defensive end]] in the [[National Football League]] (NFL) for the [[Atlanta Falcons]] and [[Philadelphia Eagles]]. Humphrey was inducted into the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] in 2014.\n\n==Professional career==\nHumphrey was [[NFL Draft|drafted]] out of [[Tennessee State University]] in the first round of the [[1968 NFL Draft]] with the third overall choice by the Falcons. Humphrey was an [[1967 College Football All-America Team|All-American]] in 1967.\n\nHumphrey's stellar career included being named First-team All-Pro five times (1971\u201374, and 1977), Second- Team All-Pro three times (1969, 1970, 1976), and All-NFC six times (1970\u201374, 1977).  He was second-team All-NFC in 1976 when Humphrey unofficially recorded a career high 15 quarterback sacks. In addition Humphrey was named to the [[Pro Bowl]] six times over the span of his career (1970\u201374 & 1977).\n\nHumphrey finished out his career with the Philadelphia Eagles from 1979\u201381. In 1980 Humphrey was a designated pass rusher, recording a team high 14\u00bd sacks helping the Eagles become NFC champions and earn a spot in [[Super Bowl XV]]. He finished his career with an unofficial 126\u00bd career sacks with the Falcons and Eagles. He retired in 1981, the season before sacks were recorded as an official NFL statistic.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}\n\nDuring Super Bowl XV, Humphrey was called for roughing the passer against [[Oakland Raiders]] quarterback [[Jim Plunkett]]. Humphrey picked up the penalty flag and fired it back at referee [[Ben Dreith]].\n\nHumphrey is a member of the Georgia Hall of Fame and the Tennessee Hall of Fame. His alma mater (Tennessee State University) retired his number and inducted him into their Hall of Fame. His high school has also retired his jersey and he is a member of his high school Hall of Fame, and is a member of the Atlanta Falcons Ring of Honor.\n\nHumphrey is a member of [[Phi Beta Sigma]].\n\n==Outside Football==\n\nClaude Humphrey also had a guest appearance on [[The Dukes of Hazzard]] episode \"Repo Men\" in which he portrayed Big John, a counterfeiter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlantafalcons.com/news/article-1/QA-with-Hall-of-Fame-DE-Claude-Humphrey/ebb05876-1d04-41af-877d-d807a771fb66|title=Q&A with Hall-of-Fame DE Claude Humphrey|author=|date=|website=atlantafalcons.com}}</ref>\n\n== Pro Football Hall of Fame ==\nHumphrey was a final 15 candidate in 2003, 2005, and 2006.  On August 27, 2008, he was named as one of two senior candidates for the 2009 Hall of Fame election.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.profootballhof.com/enshrinement/story.jsp?story_id=2816 |title=Archived copy |access-date=September 3, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080903085641/http://www.profootballhof.com/enshrinement/story.jsp?story_id=2816 |archive-date=September 3, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  In August 2013, he was named as one of two senior candidates for the 2014 Hall of Fame election.\n\nIn February 2014, Claude Humphrey was elected to the Pro Football Hall of Fame on the senior ballot. During his time in football, Humphrey was a revolutionary pass rushing defensive lineman who paved the way for Reggie White, Bruce Smith, and fellow 2014 NFL HOF inductee Michael Strahan.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n\nOn August 2, 2014, Humphrey was officially inducted at the Enshrienment Ceremony where his bust, sculpted by [[Scott Myers]], was unveiled.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/member.jsp?player_id=245 Biography] as a finalist for the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] in 2006.\n\n{{1968 NFL Draft}}\n{{FalconsFirstPick}}\n{{Atlanta Falcons 1968 draft navbox}}\n{{AP Defensive Rookies of the Year}}\n{{Atlanta Falcons}}\n{{2014 Football HOF}}\n{{Pro Football Hall of Fame members}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Humphrey, Claude}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football defensive ends]]\n[[Category:Atlanta Falcons players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Eagles players]]\n[[Category:Tennessee State Tigers football players]]\n[[Category:National Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:National Football League Defensive Rookie of the Year Award winners]]\n[[Category:NFL Europe (WLAF) coaches]]\n[[Category:Pro Football Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Tennessee]]\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "Enshrienment->Enshrinement -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Humphrey"}
{"title_page": "Kristang people", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}{{Short description|ethnic group}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group      = Kristang people<br /><small>Orang Kristang / Serani / Jenti Kristang</small>\n|image      = [[File:Kristangi Malacca.jpg|300px]]\n|caption    = A group of Kristang people performing a traditional dance in Malacca, Malaysia.\n|population = 37,000<ref>https://www.lonelyplanet.com/malaysia-singapore-brunei/background/other-features/8f3253aa-2294-4762-8523-e9c20d3f636b/a/nar/8f3253aa-2294-4762-8523-e9c20d3f636b/1325999</ref>\n|popplace   = {{Flag|Malaysia}} ([[Malacca]], [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Penang]])<br>{{Flag|Singapore}} \n|langs      = [[Kristang language|Papia Kristang]], [[English language|English]], [[Malay language|Malay]]\n|rels       = Predominantly [[Christianity]] ([[Roman Catholic]]), minority [[Judaism]] and [[Secular]]\n|related    = [[Eurasian (mixed ancestry)|Eurasian]], [[Mardijker]], [[Goan Catholics]], [[Portuguese people#Portuguese diaspora|Portuguese diaspora]], [[Bumiputera (Malaysia)|Bumiputera]], [[History of the Jews in Malaysia|Jews]]\n}}\n\nThe '''''Kristang''''' (otherwise known as \"Portuguese-Eurasians\" or \"Malacca Portuguese\") are a [[Creole peoples|creole]] ethnic group of people of mixed [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]] and [[Malacca]]n descent based in [[Malaysia]] and to some extent in [[Singapore]]. People of this ethnicity have, besides Portuguese, a strong [[Dutch people|Dutch]] heritage, as well as some [[British people|British]], [[Malaysian Malay|Malay]], [[Chinese Malaysian|Chinese]] and [[Malaysian Indian|Indian]] heritage due to intermarriages, which is common among the Kristang. In addition, due to perseccution by the [[Portuguese Inquisition]] in the region, a lot of the [[History of the Jews in Malaysia| Jews of Malacca]] assimilated into the Kristang community.<ref>Humanistic & Secular Jews Build Communities and Congregations Worldwide: Malaysia {{cite web |url=http://ifshj.net/id5.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-12-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101027214511/http://ifshj.net/id5.html |archivedate=27 October 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The creole group arose in [[Portuguese Malacca|Malacca]] (part of present-day [[Malaysia]]) between the 16th and 17th centuries, when the city was a port and base of the [[Portuguese Empire]]. Some descendants speak a distinctive [[Kristang language]] or Malacca Portuguese, a [[creole language|creole]] based on [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]. Today the government classifies them as Portuguese Eurasians.\n\nThe Kristang language is formally called Malacca-Melayu Portuguese Creole, made up of elements of each.<ref>[http://www.joanmarbeck.net/ ''Language Is the Soul of our Kristang Heritage''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090528091418/http://www.joanmarbeck.net/ |date=28 May 2009 }}, Joan Marbeck Website, accessed 12 June 2009.</ref>  The Malay language, or ''Bahasa Melayu'', has changed to incorporate many Kristang words. For example, ''garfu'' ([[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]: ''garfo'') is Kristang for \"fork\" and ''almari''  ([[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]: ''arm\u00e1rio'') is Kristang for \"cupboard\"; the Malay language incorporated these Kristang words whole.\n\nScholars believe the Kristang community originated in part from liaisons and marriages between Portuguese men (sailors, soldiers, traders, etc.) and local native women. The men came to Malacca during the [[Portugal in the Age of Discovery|age of Portuguese explorations]], and in the early colonial years, Portuguese women did not settle in the colony. Nowadays intermarriage occurs more frequently between Kristang and people of Chinese and Indian ethnicity rather than Malay because of [[endogamous]] religious laws. These require non-Muslims intending to marry Malay-Muslims first to convert to Islam. Eurasians are not always willing to alter their religious and cultural identity in this way. In earlier centuries, Portuguese and local Malays were able to marry without such conversions, because such religious laws did not exist.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\nThe name \"Kristang\" is sometimes incorrectly used for other [[Eurasian Singaporean|people of mixed European and Asian descent]] presently living in Malaysia and Singapore. This includes people of  Portuguese descent who were not part of the historical Kristang community, and people with other European ancestry, such as [[Dutch people|Dutch]] or [[British diaspora|British]].\n\nThe name comes from  the Portuguese creole ''Kristang'' (Christian), derived from the [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] ''Crist\u00e3o''. A [[derogatory term]] for the Malacca Portuguese community was ''Grago'' or ''Gragok'' (slang term for Portuguese ''camar\u00e3o'' (shrimp), referring to the fact that the Portuguese Malaccans were traditionally shrimp fishermen).<ref>Julian Wong, \"When Exactly Can You Call an Eurasian a \u2018Grago\u2019?\" [https://www.ricemedia.co/culture-life-when-exactly-can-you-call-an-eurasian-a-grago]/</ref> In the native tongue, they also call themselves '''Gente Kristang''' (Christian people).\n\n==History==\n\n===Portuguese expeditions===\nMalacca was a major destination in the great wave of sea expeditions launched by [[Portugal]] around the turn of the 16th century. It eventually was controlled as part of the [[Portuguese Empire]]. The first Portuguese expedition to reach Malacca landed in 1507. The ''Sejarah Melayu'' (''[[Malay Annals]]'') noted that the Malays first called them ''Bengali Puteh'' (White Bengalis), as the Portuguese brought to mind traders from Bengal but were more pale skinned. In the early years, the Malays called the Portuguese '''Serani''' (a Malay contraction of the Arabic ''[[Nasrani (Arabic term for Christian)|Nasrani]]'', meaning followers of [[Jesus]] the Nazarene).<ref>[http://www.lusotopie.sciencespobordeaux.fr/fernandis.pdf Gerard Fernandis, \"Paipia, Relijang e Tradisang\" (People, Religion and Tradition), The Portuguese Eurasians in Malayasia: 'Bumiquest', \"A Search for Self Identity\"], ''Lusotopie'', 2000, Sciences Politiques - Bordeaux, accessed 12 June 2009.</ref>  A story was recorded that the Portuguese landing party inadvertently insulted the Malaccan [[sultan]] by placing a [[garland]] of flowers on his head, and he had them detained. In 1511, a Portuguese fleet came from [[Portuguese India|India]] to free the landing party and [[Capture of Malacca (1511)|conquer Malacca]].\n\nAt that time, Portuguese women were barred from travelling overseas due to superstition about women on ships, as well as the substantial danger of the sea route around [[Cape of Good Hope]]. Following the Portuguese colonization of [[Sultanate of Malacca|Malacca]] ([[Malaysia]]) in 1511, the Portuguese government encouraged their explorers to marry local indigenous women, under a policy set by [[Afonso de Albuquerque]], then [[Viceroy]] of [[Portuguese India|India]]. To promote settlement, the King of Portugal granted freeman status and exemption from Crown taxes to Portuguese men (known as ''casados'', or \"married men\") who ventured overseas and married local women. With Albuquerque's encouragement, mixed marriages flourished and some 200 were recorded by 1604. By creating families, the Portuguese men would make more settled communities, with families whose children would be Catholic and loyal to the Crown.\n\n===The Dutch takeover===\nA powerful sea power, the rising [[Dutch Republic|Dutch]] nation took Malacca from the Portuguese in 1641. This coincided with the [[Portuguese Restoration War]] in Portugal that ended the 60-year period known as the \"Union of the Crowns\" (1580\u20131640), when the crown of Portugal was joined with the crown of Spain by [[personal union]]. Almost all political contact between Portugal and Malacca ended, and a large number of people of Portuguese descent in the city were evacuated to [[Batavia, Dutch East Indies|Batavia]](now Jakarta), the [[Dutch East India Company]] headquarters, as war captives, where they settled in an area called \"[[Koja, Jakarta|Kampung Tugu]]\".<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=East of Bali: From Lombok to Timor|author1=M\u00fcller, K.|author2=Pickell, D.|date=1997|publisher=Periplus|isbn=9789625931784|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DSmqaNFttVkC|page=217|accessdate=2 March 2015}}</ref>  Portuguese trade relations with the former colonial outpost of Macau have continued to this day.\n\nEven after Portugal lost Malacca in 1641, the Kristang community largely preserved its traditions, practicing [[Catholicism]] and using the Portuguese language within the community. Some [[Roman Catholicism in the Netherlands|Dutch crypto-Catholics]] were also absorbed into the community during this time.\n\n==Present status==\nThe Kristang community still has cultural and linguistic continuities with today's Portugal, especially with the [[Minho Province|Minho]] region, from where many early settlers emigrated. The Kristang continue to hold some church services in [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], and Malaysians, including themselves, often refer to the community as \"Portuguese\". As the Kristang language is not taught in schools, it is nearing extinction, with the exception of within the [[Portuguese Settlement, Malacca|Portuguese Settlement]] in ''[[Portuguese Settlement, Malacca|Ujong Pasir Malacca]]''.\n\nThe Kristang people in Malaysia do not have full ''[[Bumiputera (Malaysia)|bumiputra]]'' status, a status which applies to [[indigenous peoples|indigenous]] [[ethnic]] groups. However they have been given the privilege to apply to be members of a trust scheme known as ''Amanah Saham Bumiputra''. This is a privilege shared by Malaysians of [[Malaysian Siamese|Thai]] descent. The government sponsored this program to help the Malays increase their participation in the national economy. The Kristang community in Singapore is part of a larger umbrella group, known generically as the [[Eurasian Singaporean|Eurasian]] community. Some members have emigrated to [[Perth, Western Australia]] over the past three decades.\n\nThe [[Portuguese Settlement, Malacca|Portuguese Settlement]] is a thriving Kristang community in Malacca, established in 1933 with the goal of gathering the dispersed Kristang community and preserving their culture. A simple village of poor fishermen for many decades, it has recently become a major tourist attraction. This has helped to improve the income of the Kristang population.\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Fishing===\nSince Portuguese times, the Kristang have been living by the sea. It is still an important part of their culture. Even today, with only 10 percent of the community earning their living by fishing, many men go fishing to supplement their income or just to relax with their neighbours. Traditionally men fish from small wooden ''[[perahu]]s'', or by pushing the ''[[langgiang]]'', a traditional [[bamboo]]-poled shrimp net through the shallows.\n\n===Music and dance===\nKristang traditional music and dance, such as the ''[[Branyo]]'' and the ''Farrapeira'' are descendants of Portuguese folk dances. The [[Branyo]], descends from the southern Portuguese folk dance [[Corridinho]], and can be easily mistaken for the Malay ''[[Joget]]'' dance, which is believed to have developed from the Branyo. The adoption of western music instruments and musical scales by traditional Malay and Indian orchestras suggests a strong Portuguese influence. The most popular branyo tune, ''Jingkli Nona'', is regarded as the unofficial \"anthem\" for Portuguese Eurasians.\n\n===Cuisine===\nKristang or Malacca Portuguese cuisine consists of heavy local influence, with the additions of stews and the inclusion of pork and seafood in the diet, and rice is the staple food. Among the many dishes in Kristang cuisine, the most popular is [[Devil's curry|Cari Debal]]. Other popular delicacies include Portuguese grilled fish, pineapple prawn Curry, Cari Seccu (dry curry), Caldu Pescador (Fisherman's soup), Sambal Chili Bedri (green chilli [[sambal]]), Soy Limang, Porku Tambrinyu (pork tamarind stew), Achar Pesi (fish pickle), Pang Su Si (Su Si Bun), and Sugee Cake. As is the custom, Kristang people commonly eat using their hands instead of utensils. It is similar to the [[Eurasian cuisine of Singapore and Malaysia]]\n\n===Names===\nThe Kristang people traditionally used [[Portuguese name|Portuguese]] and Christian first names, while their surnames were Portuguese. Among the many common surnames are [[Fernandes]], [[Lopes]], [[Santamaria (disambiguation)|Santa Maria]], [[Siqueira]], [[Costa (surname)|De Costa]], [[Pereira (surname)|Pereira]], [[Teixeira]], [[Gomes]] and [[Pinto (disambiguation)|Pinto]].\n\n==Religion==\nIn general the Kristang practice [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholicism]]. [[Christmas]] (''Natal'') is the most festive occasion of the year, when many Kristang families get together to celebrate by eating seasonal dishes, singing  [[Carol (music)|carols]] and ''branyok'', and revelling in ''[[saudade|saudadi]]''. Like many other Portuguese-speaking Catholic communities around the world, the Kristang also celebrate a string of major [[Calendar of saints|Saints' days]] at the end of June, beginning with [[John the Baptist|St. John]] (''San Juang'') on 24 June and closing with [[Peter the Apostle|St. Peter]] (''San Pedro''), the fishermen's [[patron saint]], on 29 June. The June festival of [[Saint John, Malacca|St. John's village]] is a major tourist attraction of Malacca. Tourists come to observe the festivities, which are religiously based. Besides that, there are also a minority of former Kristang Christians who had rediscovered their Sephardic Jewish roots and returned to Judaism. This led to the establishment of the Kristang Community for Cultural [[Judaism]] (KCCJ) in 2010 which is no longer in operation due to political reasons.\n\n==Portuguese influence on Malay language==\nThe Portuguese ruled Malacca from 1511 to 1641. About 300 Portuguese words were adopted in the Malay language. These include:\n* ''kereta'' (from ''carreta'', car);\n* ''sekolah'' (from ''escola'', school);\n* ''bendera'' (from ''bandeira'', flag);\n* ''mentega'' (from ''manteiga'', butter);\n* ''keju'' (from ''queijo'', cheese);\n* ''gereja'' (from ''igreja'', church);\n* ''meja'' (from ''mesa'', table); and\n* ''nenas'' (from ''anan\u00e1s'', pineapple).\n\n==Notable Kristang people==\n\n'''Malaysian'''\n*[[Joan Margaret Marbeck]] - a Malaysian scholar specializing in the study of the Malay-Portuguese Creole language [[Kristang language]]\nin Malaysia and other countries ([[Singapore]], [[Australia]], [[Macau]]).\n*[[Marion Caunter]] - TV personality\n*[[Bernard Sta Maria]] - Author of 'The Golden Son of Kadazan' and 'My People My Country' - Malacca Portuguese leader/politician\n*[[Joseph Sta Maria]] - Author of 'Undi Nos By Di Aki' (Where Do We Go From Here?) - Portuguese community advisor/social activist.\n* [[Peter van Huizen]] - Malaysian hockey goalkeeper (1956 Olympics).\n* [[Tan Sri Tony Fernandes]] - CEO of Air Asia (Maternal).\n* [[Dr. Siri Roland Xavier]] - Well known Malaysian International Professor of Entrepreneurship.\n* [[Datuk Eugene Campos]] - The Hon. Consul of Portugal & Patron of S.A.F.T.E.A. (Selangor and Federal Territory Eurasian Association). Well known businessman.\n*[[William Noel Clark]] - Malaysian musician - Represented Malaysia in 1987 Asian Broadcasting Union (ABU) competition.\n*[[Brian J. Chong]] - Public Relations Expert\n*[[Larry Rodrigues]]- Better known by many as Uncle Larry, he was by far one of the leading jazz guitarists in the country. Started playing with Jimmy Boyle in the 1940s at the Runnymede, Sandycroft and the Penang Club for more than 20 years. After the death of Jimmy Boyle, Larry led the band with Steve (Rozells) Ooi on piano, and continued performing at the Penang Club until he had a stroke while performing at the club in 1981. All through the years, Larry Rodrigues thrilled audiences in pubs, hotels and clubs with his style of playing and till today many guitarists still remember and marvel at the guitar playing style of Larry Rodrigues. Uncle Larry also made numerous recordings with Radio Malaysia where he played many of Jimmy Boyle\u2019s compositions. Larry\u2019s proudest musical moment was when the great American jazz guitarist Charlie Byrd performed in Penang in the 1970s and invited Larry to jam with him.\n*Tan Sri Dr. Rebecca Fatima Sta. Maria - Former Secretary General of the [[Ministry of International Trade and Industry]] (MITI) (2010-2016). She became the first female secretary general of the ministry and later the first woman to lead [[Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation|APEC]] secretariat.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2016/07/03/an-illustrious-pioneer-leaving-a-sterling-career-in-the-civil-service-after-35-years-tan-sri-dr-rebe/ |title=An illustrious pioneer |publisher=The Star Online|date=3 July 2016|author1=Mergawati Zulfakar|author2=Desiree Gasper|accessdate=30 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/11/15/former-miti-sec-gen-is-first-woman-to-lead-apec-secretariat |title=Former Miti sec-gen is first woman to lead APEC secretariat\n|publisher=The Star Online|date=15 November 2018|author1=|author2=|accessdate=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Jeanne Abdullah|Tun Jeanne Abdullah]] - Wife of former [[Prime Minister of Malaysia]], [[Tun Abdullah Ahmad Badawi]].\n*[[Kimberley Leggett]] - [[Miss Universe]] [[Malaysia]] 2012.\n*[[Sharon Alaina Stephen]] - Actress in [[Disney]]'s [[Waktu Rehat]].\n*[[Andrea Fonseka]] - Model and TV presenter. Also Miss Universe Malaysia 2004 and daughter of former Miss Universe Malaysia, Datin Josephine Fonseka.\n*Chef Melba Nunis - [[Chef]] and the writer of ''A Kristang Family Cookbook'', winner of 2016 Gourmand World Cookbook Awards (GWCA) Best in the World in the Woman Chef category.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2016/06/01/boost-for-kristang-cuisine-chef-nunis-cookbook-wins-prestigious-global-award/ |title=Chef Nunis\u2019 cookbook wins prestigious global award |publisher=The Star Online|date=1 June 2016|author=Suzanne Lazaroo|accessdate=30 June 2018}}</ref>\n \n'''Singaporean'''\n* [[Bernard Rodrigues]] (1933-2015), Singaporean politician - founding member of the [[People's Action Party]] and leader of the NTUC (National Trades Union Congress).\n* [[Jeremy Monteiro]] - Singaporean jazz pianist, singer, composer and music educator.\n'''Australian'''\n* [[Guy Sebastian]] - Malaysian born Australian singer.\n* Sarah Marbeck - Malaysian born Australian model.\n* [[Royston Sta Maria]] - Well known singer and songwriter from Malaysia.\n'''British'''\n* [[Aaron Sequerah]] - Malaysian born Australian-British Comedian, Actor and former member of the indie-rock band \u201c[[Mnemonic (band)]]\u201d.\n'''Philippines'''\n* [[Monika Santa Maria]] - Filipino model who finished as 1st runner-up in third season of [[Asia's Next Top Model]].\n\n==See also (Related ethnic groups)==\n*[[Eurasian (mixed ancestry)|Eurasian]] \u2013 various ethnic groups of mixed European-Asian ancestry\n*[[Anglo-Burmese people]] - ethnic group from [[Myanmar]]\n*[[Burgher people]] - ethnic group from [[Sri Lanka]]\n*[[Eurasian Singaporean]] - ethnic group from [[Singapore]]\n*[[Filipino mestizo]] - ethnic group from the [[Philippines]]\n*[[Indo people]] - ethnic group from [[Indonesia]]\n*[[Macanese people]] - ethnic group from Macau usually with some Portuguese ancestry\n*[[Mardijker people]] - ethnic group from [[Indonesia]] with Portuguese ancestry\n*[[East Indians]] - Ethnic group from [[Mumbai, India]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.lusotopie.sciencespobordeaux.fr/fernandis.pdf Gerard Fernandis, \"Paipia, Relijang e Tradisang\" (People, Religion and Tradition), The Portuguese Eurasians in Malayasia: 'Bumiquest', \"A Search for Self Identity\"], ''Lusotopie'', 2000, Sciences Politiques - Bordeaux\n*[http://www.penangstory.net.my/mino-content-paperanthony.html \"Penang Eurasians\"], Penang Story\n*[http://www.todayonline.com/world/asia/malacca-loses-kristang-singapore-group-seeks-revive-500-year-old-language As Malacca loses Kristang, Singapore group seeks to revive 500-year-old language]\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Malaysia}}\n{{Indians in Malaysia}}\n{{Portuguese diaspora}}\n\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:European diaspora in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Kristang people|*]]\n[[Category:Multiracial affairs in Asia]]\n[[Category:Portuguese diaspora in Asia]]\n[[Category:Immigration to Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Kristang descent| ]]\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Indian descent|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}{{Short description|ethnic group}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group      = Kristang people<br /><small>Orang Kristang / Serani / Jenti Kristang</small>\n|image      = [[File:Kristangi Malacca.jpg|300px]]\n|caption    = A group of Kristang people performing a traditional dance in Malacca, Malaysia.\n|population = 37,000<ref>https://www.lonelyplanet.com/malaysia-singapore-brunei/background/other-features/8f3253aa-2294-4762-8523-e9c20d3f636b/a/nar/8f3253aa-2294-4762-8523-e9c20d3f636b/1325999</ref>\n|popplace   = {{Flag|Malaysia}} ([[Malacca]], [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Penang]])<br>{{Flag|Singapore}} \n|langs      = [[Kristang language|Papia Kristang]], [[English language|English]], [[Malay language|Malay]]\n|rels       = Predominantly [[Christianity]] ([[Roman Catholic]]), minority [[Judaism]] and [[Secular]]\n|related    = [[Eurasian (mixed ancestry)|Eurasian]], [[Mardijker]], [[Goan Catholics]], [[Portuguese people#Portuguese diaspora|Portuguese diaspora]], [[Bumiputera (Malaysia)|Bumiputera]], [[History of the Jews in Malaysia|Jews]]\n}}\n\nThe '''''Kristang''''' (otherwise known as \"Portuguese-Eurasians\" or \"Malacca Portuguese\") are a [[Creole peoples|creole]] ethnic group of people of mixed [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]] and [[Malacca]]n descent based in [[Malaysia]] and to some extent in [[Singapore]]. People of this ethnicity have, besides Portuguese, a strong [[Dutch people|Dutch]] heritage, as well as some [[British people|British]], [[Malaysian Malay|Malay]], [[Chinese Malaysian|Chinese]] and [[Malaysian Indian|Indian]] heritage due to intermarriages, which is common among the Kristang. In addition, due to perseccution by the [[Portuguese Inquisition]] in the region, a lot of the [[History of the Jews in Malaysia| Jews of Malacca]] assimilated into the Kristang community.<ref>Humanistic & Secular Jews Build Communities and Congregations Worldwide: Malaysia {{cite web |url=http://ifshj.net/id5.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-12-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101027214511/http://ifshj.net/id5.html |archivedate=27 October 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The creole group arose in [[Portuguese Malacca|Malacca]] (part of present-day [[Malaysia]]) between the 16th and 17th centuries, when the city was a port and base of the [[Portuguese Empire]]. Some descendants speak a distinctive [[Kristang language]] or Malacca Portuguese, a [[creole language|creole]] based on [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]. Today the government classifies them as Portuguese Eurasians.\n\nThe Kristang language is formally called Malacca-Melayu Portuguese Creole, made up of elements of each.<ref>[http://www.joanmarbeck.net/ ''Language Is the Soul of our Kristang Heritage''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090528091418/http://www.joanmarbeck.net/ |date=28 May 2009 }}, Joan Marbeck Website, accessed 12 June 2009.</ref>  The Malay language, or ''Bahasa Melayu'', has changed to incorporate many Kristang words. For example, ''garfu'' ([[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]: ''garfo'') is Kristang for \"fork\" and ''almari''  ([[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]: ''arm\u00e1rio'') is Kristang for \"cupboard\"; the Malay language incorporated these Kristang words whole.\n\nScholars believe the Kristang community originated in part from liaisons and marriages between Portuguese men (sailors, soldiers, traders, etc.) and local native women. The men came to Malacca during the [[Portugal in the Age of Discovery|age of Portuguese explorations]], and in the early colonial years, Portuguese women did not settle in the colony. Nowadays intermarriage occurs more frequently between Kristang and people of Chinese and Indian ethnicity rather than Malay because of [[endogamous]] religious laws. These require non-Muslims intending to marry Malay-Muslims first to convert to Islam. Eurasians are not always willing to alter their religious and cultural identity in this way. In earlier centuries, Portuguese and local Malays were able to marry without such conversions, because such religious laws did not exist.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\nThe name \"Kristang\" is sometimes incorrectly used for other [[Eurasian Singaporean|people of mixed European and Asian descent]] presently living in Malaysia and Singapore. This includes people of  Portuguese descent who were not part of the historical Kristang community, and people with other European ancestry, such as [[Dutch people|Dutch]] or [[British diaspora|British]].\n\nThe name comes from  the Portuguese creole ''Kristang'' (Christian), derived from the [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] ''Crist\u00e3o''. A [[derogatory term]] for the Malacca Portuguese community was ''Grago'' or ''Gragok'' (slang term for Portuguese ''camar\u00e3o'' (shrimp), referring to the fact that the Portuguese Malaccans were traditionally shrimp fishermen).<ref>Julian Wong, \"When Exactly Can You Call an Eurasian a \u2018Grago\u2019?\" [https://www.ricemedia.co/culture-life-when-exactly-can-you-call-an-eurasian-a-grago]/</ref> In the native tongue, they also call themselves '''Gente Kristang''' (Christian people).\n\n==History==\n\n===Portuguese expeditions===\nMalacca was a major destination in the great wave of sea expeditions launched by [[Portugal]] around the turn of the 16th century. It eventually was controlled as part of the [[Portuguese Empire]]. The first Portuguese expedition to reach Malacca landed in 1507. The ''Sejarah Melayu'' (''[[Malay Annals]]'') noted that the Malays first called them ''Bengali Puteh'' (White Bengalis), as the Portuguese brought to mind traders from Bengal but were more pale skinned. In the early years, the Malays called the Portuguese '''Serani''' (a Malay contraction of the Arabic ''[[Nasrani (Arabic term for Christian)|Nasrani]]'', meaning followers of [[Jesus]] the Nazarene).<ref>[http://www.lusotopie.sciencespobordeaux.fr/fernandis.pdf Gerard Fernandis, \"Paipia, Relijang e Tradisang\" (People, Religion and Tradition), The Portuguese Eurasians in Malayasia: 'Bumiquest', \"A Search for Self Identity\"], ''Lusotopie'', 2000, Sciences Politiques - Bordeaux, accessed 12 June 2009.</ref>  A story was recorded that the Portuguese landing party inadvertently insulted the Malaccan [[sultan]] by placing a [[garland]] of flowers on his head, and he had them detained. In 1511, a Portuguese fleet came from [[Portuguese India|India]] to free the landing party and [[Capture of Malacca (1511)|conquer Malacca]].\n\nAt that time, Portuguese women were barred from travelling overseas due to superstition about women on ships, as well as the substantial danger of the sea route around [[Cape of Good Hope]]. Following the Portuguese colonization of [[Sultanate of Malacca|Malacca]] ([[Malaysia]]) in 1511, the Portuguese government encouraged their explorers to marry local indigenous women, under a policy set by [[Afonso de Albuquerque]], then [[Viceroy]] of [[Portuguese India|India]]. To promote settlement, the King of Portugal granted freeman status and exemption from Crown taxes to Portuguese men (known as ''casados'', or \"married men\") who ventured overseas and married local women. With Albuquerque's encouragement, mixed marriages flourished and some 200 were recorded by 1604. By creating families, the Portuguese men would make more settled communities, with families whose children would be Catholic and loyal to the Crown.\n\n===The Dutch takeover===\nA powerful sea power, the rising [[Dutch Republic|Dutch]] nation took Malacca from the Portuguese in 1641. This coincided with the [[Portuguese Restoration War]] in Portugal that ended the 60-year period known as the \"Union of the Crowns\" (1580\u20131640), when the crown of Portugal was joined with the crown of Spain by [[personal union]]. Almost all political contact between Portugal and Malacca ended, and a large number of people of Portuguese descent in the city were evacuated to [[Batavia, Dutch East Indies|Batavia]](now Jakarta), the [[Dutch East India Company]] headquarters, as war captives, where they settled in an area called \"[[Koja, Jakarta|Kampung Tugu]]\".<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=East of Bali: From Lombok to Timor|author1=M\u00fcller, K.|author2=Pickell, D.|date=1997|publisher=Periplus|isbn=9789625931784|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DSmqaNFttVkC|page=217|accessdate=2 March 2015}}</ref>  Portuguese trade relations with the former colonial outpost of Macau have continued to this day.\n\nEven after Portugal lost Malacca in 1641, the Kristang community largely preserved its traditions, practicing [[Catholicism]] and using the Portuguese language within the community. Some [[Roman Catholicism in the Netherlands|Dutch crypto-Catholics]] were also absorbed into the community during this time.\n\n==Present status==\nThe Kristang community still has cultural and linguistic continuities with today's Portugal, especially with the [[Minho Province|Minho]] region, from where many early settlers emigrated. The Kristang continue to hold some church services in [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], and Malaysians, including themselves, often refer to the community as \"Portuguese\". As the Kristang language is not taught in schools, it is nearing extinction, with the exception of within the [[Portuguese Settlement, Malacca|Portuguese Settlement]] in ''[[Portuguese Settlement, Malacca|Ujong Pasir Malacca]]''.\n\nThe Kristang people in Malaysia do not have full ''[[Bumiputera (Malaysia)|bumiputra]]'' status, a status which applies to [[indigenous peoples|indigenous]] [[ethnic]] groups. However they have been given the privilege to apply to be members of a trust scheme known as ''Amanah Saham Bumiputra''. This is a privilege shared by Malaysians of [[Malaysian Siamese|Thai]] descent. The government sponsored this program to help the Malays increase their participation in the national economy. The Kristang community in Singapore is part of a larger umbrella group, known generically as the [[Eurasian Singaporean|Eurasian]] community. Some members have emigrated to [[Perth, Western Australia]] over the past three decades.\n\nThe [[Portuguese Settlement, Malacca|Portuguese Settlement]] is a thriving Kristang community in Malacca, established in 1933 with the goal of gathering the dispersed Kristang community and preserving their culture. A simple village of poor fishermen for many decades, it has recently become a major tourist attraction. This has helped to improve the income of the Kristang population.\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Fishing===\nSince Portuguese times, the Kristang have been living by the sea. It is still an important part of their culture. Even today, with only 10 percent of the community earning their living by fishing, many men go fishing to supplement their income or just to relax with their neighbours. Traditionally men fish from small wooden ''[[perahu]]s'', or by pushing the ''[[langgiang]]'', a traditional [[bamboo]]-poled shrimp net through the shallows.\n\n===Music and dance===\nKristang traditional music and dance, such as the ''[[Branyo]]'' and the ''Farrapeira'' are descendants of Portuguese folk dances. The [[Branyo]], descends from the southern Portuguese folk dance [[Corridinho]], and can be easily mistaken for the Malay ''[[Joget]]'' dance, which is believed to have developed from the Branyo. The adoption of western music instruments and musical scales by traditional Malay and Indian orchestras suggests a strong Portuguese influence. The most popular branyo tune, ''Jingkli Nona'', is regarded as the unofficial \"anthem\" for Portuguese Eurasians.\n\n===Cuisine===\nKristang or Malacca Portuguese cuisine consists of heavy local influence, with the additions of stews and the inclusion of pork and seafood in the diet, and rice is the staple food. Among the many dishes in Kristang cuisine, the most popular is [[Devil's curry|Cari Debal]]. Other popular delicacies include Portuguese grilled fish, pineapple prawn Curry, Cari Seccu (dry curry), Caldu Pescador (Fisherman's soup), Sambal Chili Bedri (green chilli [[sambal]]), Soy Limang, Porku Tambrinyu (pork tamarind stew), Achar Pesi (fish pickle), Pang Su Si (Su Si Bun), and Sugee Cake. As is the custom, Kristang people commonly eat using their hands instead of utensils. It is similar to the [[Eurasian cuisine of Singapore and Malaysia]]\n\n===Names===\nThe Kristang people traditionally used [[Portuguese name|Portuguese]] and Christian first names, while their surnames were Portuguese. Among the many common surnames are [[Fernandes]], [[Lopes]], [[Santamaria (disambiguation)|Santa Maria]], [[Siqueira]], [[Costa (surname)|De Costa]], [[Pereira (surname)|Pereira]], [[Teixeira]], [[Gomes]] and [[Pinto (disambiguation)|Pinto]].\n\n==Religion==\nIn general the Kristang practice [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholicism]]. [[Christmas]] (''Natal'') is the most festive occasion of the year, when many Kristang families get together to celebrate by eating seasonal dishes, singing  [[Carol (music)|carols]] and ''branyok'', and revelling in ''[[saudade|saudadi]]''. Like many other Portuguese-speaking Catholic communities around the world, the Kristang also celebrate a string of major [[Calendar of saints|Saints' days]] at the end of June, beginning with [[John the Baptist|St. John]] (''San Juang'') on 24 June and closing with [[Peter the Apostle|St. Peter]] (''San Pedro''), the fishermen's [[patron saint]], on 29 June. The June festival of [[Saint John, Malacca|St. John's village]] is a major tourist attraction of Malacca. Tourists come to observe the festivities, which are religiously based. Besides that, there are also a minority of former Kristang Christians who had rediscovered their Sephardic Jewish roots and returned to Judaism. This led to the establishment of the Kristang Community for Cultural [[Judaism]] (KCCJ) in 2010 which is no longer in operation due to political reasons.\n\n==Portuguese influence on Malay language==\nThe Portuguese ruled Malacca from 1511 to 1641. About 300 Portuguese words were adopted in the Malay language. These include:\n* ''kereta'' (from ''carreta'', car);\n* ''sekolah'' (from ''escola'', school);\n* ''bendera'' (from ''bandeira'', flag);\n* ''mentega'' (from ''manteiga'', butter);\n* ''keju'' (from ''queijo'', cheese);\n* ''gereja'' (from ''igreja'', church);\n* ''meja'' (from ''mesa'', table); and\n* ''nenas'' (from ''anan\u00e1s'', pineapple).\n\n==Notable Kristang people==\n\n'''Malaysian'''\n*[[Joan Margaret Marbeck]] - a Malaysian scholar specializing in the study of the Malay-Portuguese Creole language [[Kristang language]]\nin Malaysia and other countries ([[Singapore]], [[Australia]], [[Macau]]).\n*[[Marion Caunter]] - TV personality\n*[[Bernard Sta Maria]] - Author of 'The Golden Son of Kadazan' and 'My People My Country' - Malacca Portuguese leader/politician\n*[[Joseph Sta Maria]] - Author of 'Undi Nos By Di Aki' (Where Do We Go From Here?) - Portuguese community advisor/social activist.\n* [[Peter van Huizen]] - Malaysian hockey goalkeeper (1956 Olympics).\n* [[Tan Sri Tony Fernandes]] - CEO of Air Asia (Maternal).\n* [[Dr. Siri Roland Xavier]] - Well known Malaysian International Professor of Entrepreneurship.\n* [[Datuk Eugene Campos]] - The Hon. Consul of Portugal & Patron of S.A.F.T.E.A. (Selangor and Federal Territory Eurasian Association). Well known businessman.\n*[[William Noel Clark]] - Malaysian musician - Represented Malaysia in 1987 Asian Broadcasting Union (ABU) competition.\n*[[Brian J. Chong]] - Public Relations Expert\n*[[Larry Rodrigues]]- Better known by many as Uncle Larry, he was by far one of the leading jazz guitarists in the country. Started playing with Jimmy Boyle in the 1940s at the Runnymede, Sandycroft and the Penang Club for more than 20 years. After the death of Jimmy Boyle, Larry led the band with Steve (Rozells) Ooi on piano, and continued performing at the Penang Club until he had a stroke while performing at the club in 1981. All through the years, Larry Rodrigues thrilled audiences in pubs, hotels and clubs with his style of playing and till today many guitarists still remember and marvel at the guitar playing style of Larry Rodrigues. Uncle Larry also made numerous recordings with Radio Malaysia where he played many of Jimmy Boyle\u2019s compositions. Larry\u2019s proudest musical moment was when the great American jazz guitarist Charlie Byrd performed in Penang in the 1970s and invited Larry to jam with him.\n*Tan Sri Dr. Rebecca Fatima Sta. Maria - Former Secretary General of the [[Ministry of International Trade and Industry]] (MITI) (2010-2016). She became the first female secretary general of the ministry and later the first woman to lead [[Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation|APEC]] secretariat.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2016/07/03/an-illustrious-pioneer-leaving-a-sterling-career-in-the-civil-service-after-35-years-tan-sri-dr-rebe/ |title=An illustrious pioneer |publisher=The Star Online|date=3 July 2016|author1=Mergawati Zulfakar|author2=Desiree Gasper|accessdate=30 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/11/15/former-miti-sec-gen-is-first-woman-to-lead-apec-secretariat |title=Former Miti sec-gen is first woman to lead APEC secretariat\n|publisher=The Star Online|date=15 November 2018|author1=|author2=|accessdate=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Jeanne Abdullah|Tun Jeanne Abdullah]] - Wife of former [[Prime Minister of Malaysia]], [[Tun Abdullah Ahmad Badawi]].\n*[[Kimberley Leggett]] - [[Miss Universe]] [[Malaysia]] 2012.\n*[[Sharon Alaina Stephen]] - Actress in [[Disney]]'s [[Waktu Rehat]].\n*[[Andrea Fonseka]] - Model and TV presenter. Also Miss Universe Malaysia 2004 and daughter of former Miss Universe Malaysia, Datin Josephine Fonseka.\n*Chef Melba Nunis - [[Chef]] and the writer of ''A Kristang Family Cookbook'', winner of 2016 Gourmand World Cookbook Awards (GWCA) Best in the World in the Woman Chef category.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2016/06/01/boost-for-kristang-cuisine-chef-nunis-cookbook-wins-prestigious-global-award/ |title=Chef Nunis\u2019 cookbook wins prestigious global award |publisher=The Star Online|date=1 June 2016|author=Suzanne Lazaroo|accessdate=30 June 2018}}</ref>\n \n'''Singaporean'''\n* [[Bernard Rodrigues]] (1933-2015), Singaporean politician - founding member of the [[People's Action Party]] and leader of the NTUC (National Trades Union Congress).\n* [[Jeremy Monteiro]] - Singaporean jazz pianist, singer, composer and music educator.\n'''Australian'''\n* [[Guy Sebastian]] - Malaysian born Australian singer.\n* [[Sarah Marbeck]] - Malaysian born Australian model.\n* [[Royston Sta Maria]] - Well known singer and songwriter from Malaysia.\n'''British'''\n* [[Aaron Sequerah]] - Malaysian born Australian-British Comedian, Actor and former member of the indie-rock band \u201c[[Mnemonic (band)]]\u201d.\n'''Philippines'''\n* [[Monika Santa Maria]] - Filipino model who finished as 1st runner-up in third season of [[Asia's Next Top Model]].\n\n==See also (Related ethnic groups)==\n*[[Eurasian (mixed ancestry)|Eurasian]] \u2013 various ethnic groups of mixed European-Asian ancestry\n*[[Anglo-Burmese people]] - ethnic group from [[Myanmar]]\n*[[Burgher people]] - ethnic group from [[Sri Lanka]]\n*[[Eurasian Singaporean]] - ethnic group from [[Singapore]]\n*[[Filipino mestizo]] - ethnic group from the [[Philippines]]\n*[[Indo people]] - ethnic group from [[Indonesia]]\n*[[Macanese people]] - ethnic group from Macau usually with some Portuguese ancestry\n*[[Mardijker people]] - ethnic group from [[Indonesia]] with Portuguese ancestry\n*[[East Indians]] - Ethnic group from [[Mumbai, India]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.lusotopie.sciencespobordeaux.fr/fernandis.pdf Gerard Fernandis, \"Paipia, Relijang e Tradisang\" (People, Religion and Tradition), The Portuguese Eurasians in Malayasia: 'Bumiquest', \"A Search for Self Identity\"], ''Lusotopie'', 2000, Sciences Politiques - Bordeaux\n*[http://www.penangstory.net.my/mino-content-paperanthony.html \"Penang Eurasians\"], Penang Story\n*[http://www.todayonline.com/world/asia/malacca-loses-kristang-singapore-group-seeks-revive-500-year-old-language As Malacca loses Kristang, Singapore group seeks to revive 500-year-old language]\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Malaysia}}\n{{Indians in Malaysia}}\n{{Portuguese diaspora}}\n\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:European diaspora in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Kristang people|*]]\n[[Category:Multiracial affairs in Asia]]\n[[Category:Portuguese diaspora in Asia]]\n[[Category:Immigration to Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Kristang descent| ]]\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Indian descent|*]]\n", "name_user": "Abenbenji", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable Kristang people", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kristang_people"}
{"title_page": "Zhasylkol Lake", "text_new": "{{short description|Lake in Kazakhstan}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{More footnotes|date=March 2020}}}}\n'''Zhasylkol Lake''' (or ''' \u0416\u0430\u0441\u044b\u043b\u043a\u04e9\u043b''') is a lake in [[Kazakhstan]]. It is on the Northern slope of the [[Dzungarian Alatau]] ridge.\n{{Infobox body of water\n| name                   = Zhasylkol Lake\n| native_name            = \u0416\u0430\u0441\u044b\u043b\u043a\u04e9\u043b\n| native_name_lang       = \n| other_name             = \n<!--    Images     -->\n| image                  = Zhasylkol Lake.jpg\n| alt                    = \n| caption                = \n| image_bathymetry       = \n| alt_bathymetry         = \n| caption_bathymetry     = \n<!--    Stats      -->\n| location               = \n| group                  = \n| coordinates            = {{coord|45.386|80.579|type:waterbody_region:KZ|display=inline,title}}\n| type                   = \n| etymology              = \n| part_of                = \n| inflow                 = \n| rivers                 = \n| outflow                = \n| oceans                 = \n| catchment              = \n| basin_countries        = \n| agency                 = \n| designation            = \n| date-built             = \n| engineer               = \n| date-flooded           = \n| length                 = \n| width                  = \n| area                   = \n| depth                  = \n| max-depth              = \n| volume                 = \n| residence_time         = \n| salinity               = \n| shore                  = \n| elevation              = \n| temperature_high       = \n| temperature_low        = \n| frozen                 = \n| islands                = \n| islands_category       = \n| sections               = \n| trenches               = \n| benches                = \n| cities                 = \n<!--      Map      -->\n| pushpin_map            = \n| pushpin_label_position = \n| pushpin_map_alt        = \n| pushpin_map_caption    = \n<!--   Below       -->\n| website                = \n| reference              = \n}}\n\n==History==\nAs a result of a catastrophic earthquake several millennia ago, a stone blockage was formed from the right slope, which blocked the course of the Kikozen river with a [[natural dam]], forming a picturesque lake. {{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Description==\nLake Zhasylkol is located on the Northern slope of the [[Dzungarian Alatau]] ridge in the valley of the Agynykatty river at an altitude of 1640 meters above sea level. People call it emerald. When the glaciers melt, the lake becomes a bright green color, especially if you look at it from above. The color of the lake's water depends not only on [[snowmelt]], but also on the time of day and weather. In spring and summer, the water is muddy the color of coffee with milk, in autumn and spring, it becomes transparent blue. At noon, the water has a turquoise hue, with a blue sky, the water becomes the color of ultramarine, in cloudy weather it becomes leaden. The greatest length of lake Superior from the North shore to the South, to the mouth of the river Aguacate is {{cvt|2.07|km}}, the greatest width in the Northern part of the lake \u2013 {{cvt|751|m}}, depth presumably {{cvt|30 to 50|m}} of mirror area \u2013 {{cvt|912,000|sqm}}. {{cvt|9|km}}, to the South, from lake Superior, the river takes Aguacate Eastern [[tributary]] of the river Ekiasha, which in turn is formed by the confluence of two small rivers \u2013 Western tributary of the river Balcony and East of a tributary of the Bark. The Kora river originates from the meltwater of the Satpayev glacier, which ends in the South with the Kara-Choki pass, along which the state border between Kazakhstan and the Republic of China runs in the latitudinal direction. The dense forest starts from the height of {{cvt|1200|m}}. Here grow fir, spruce, aspen, birch and poplar. It is here in Dzungaria that the most apple trees in [[Kazakhstan]] remain (49%), including the [[Malus sieversii|Sievers apple]] tree, which is the ancestor of all most domestic apple trees on Earth.\n\nOn the shores of the lake, deciduous groves have grown, which acquire a special beauty in autumn. The area of lake Zhasylkol is an excellent habitat for a large population of marals. Until the eighties of the last century, almost no human set foot here, which is not surprising, because the state border between [[China]] and [[Kazakhstan]] passes here. Traveling here is a great opportunity where virgin nature is evident with its magical views.\n\nThe lake is located in Zhetysu Alatau, {{cvt|23|km}} southwest of the village of [[Lepsinsk]], in the middle reaches of the Kikozen river, one of the sources of the Agynykatty river. From the wheat apiary to the lake along the path winding along the valley of the Agynykatty river \u2013 about {{cvt|10|km}}, from the lake to the Jaeger cordon Zhalanash more than {{cvt|13|km}}.\nThe object is part of the state national nature Park Zhongar-Alatau<ref name=\"sarkan-zhongaralatau-kz\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sarkan-zhongaralatau-kz.online|title=\u041c\u043e\u044f \u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 - www.sarkan-zhongaralatau-kz.online|website=sarkan-zhongaralatau-kz.online|accessdate=2020-03-22}}</ref> and has a favorable acoustic environment (e.g. silence and melodic sounds in nature). The best time to travel is from May to October\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n===Sources===\n*A. A. Akhmatov, A. G. Pozdeyev Guide to the Almaty region. Almaty, 2012\n*[https://bb.kaznu.kz/index.php/biology/article/view/1062 M. Zh. Zhandaev Nature Of The TRANS-Ili Alatau.Almaty, \"Kazakhstan\", 1978]\n\n{{Lakes of Kazakhstan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zhasylkol Lake}}\n[[Category:Lakes of Kazakhstan]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Lake in Kazakhstan}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{lead missing|date=March 2020}}\n{{More footnotes|date=March 2020}}\n}}\n'''Zhasylkol Lake''' (or ''' \u0416\u0430\u0441\u044b\u043b\u043a\u04e9\u043b''') is a lake in [[Kazakhstan]].  It is on the Northern slope of the [[Dzungarian Alatau]] ridge.\n{{Infobox body of water\n| name                   = Zhasylkol Lake\n| native_name            = \u0416\u0430\u0441\u044b\u043b\u043a\u04e9\u043b\n| native_name_lang       = \n| other_name             = \n<!--    Images     -->\n| image                  = Zhasylkol Lake.jpg\n| alt                    = \n| caption                = \n| image_bathymetry       = \n| alt_bathymetry         = \n| caption_bathymetry     = \n<!--    Stats      -->\n| location               = \n| group                  = \n| coordinates            = {{coord|45.386|80.579|type:waterbody_region:KZ|display=inline,title}}\n| type                   = \n| etymology              = \n| part_of                = \n| inflow                 = \n| rivers                 = \n| outflow                = \n| oceans                 = \n| catchment              = \n| basin_countries        = \n| agency                 = \n| designation            = \n| date-built             = \n| engineer               = \n| date-flooded           = \n| length                 = \n| width                  = \n| area                   = \n| depth                  = \n| max-depth              = \n| volume                 = \n| residence_time         = \n| salinity               = \n| shore                  = \n| elevation              = \n| temperature_high       = \n| temperature_low        = \n| frozen                 = \n| islands                = \n| islands_category       = \n| sections               = \n| trenches               = \n| benches                = \n| cities                 = \n<!--      Map      -->\n| pushpin_map            = \n| pushpin_label_position = \n| pushpin_map_alt        = \n| pushpin_map_caption    = \n<!--   Below       -->\n| website                = \n| reference              = \n}}\n\n==History==\nAs a result of a catastrophic earthquake several millennia ago, a stone blockage was formed from the right slope, which blocked the course of the Kikozen river with a [[natural dam]], forming a picturesque lake.\n\n==Description==\nLake Zhasylkol is located on the Northern slope of the [[Dzungarian Alatau]] ridge in the valley of the Agynykatty river at an altitude of 1640 meters above sea level. People call it emerald. When the glaciers melt, the lake becomes a bright green color, especially if you look at it from above. The color of the lake's water depends not only on [[snowmelt]], but also on the time of day and weather. In spring and summer, the water is muddy the color of coffee with milk, in autumn and spring, it becomes transparent blue. At noon, the water has a turquoise hue, with a blue sky, the water becomes the color of ultramarine, in cloudy weather it becomes leaden. The greatest length of lake Superior from the North shore to the South, to the mouth of the river Aguacate is {{cvt|2.07|km}}, the greatest width in the Northern part of the lake \u2013 {{cvt|751|m}}, depth presumably {{cvt|30 to 50|m}} of mirror area \u2013 {{cvt|912,000|sqm}}. {{cvt|9|km}}, to the South, from lake Superior, the river takes Aguacate Eastern [[tributary]] of the river Ekiasha, which in turn is formed by the confluence of two small rivers \u2013 Western tributary of the river Balcony and East of a tributary of the Bark. The Kora river originates from the meltwater of the Satpayev glacier, which ends in the South with the Kara-Choki pass, along which the state border between Kazakhstan and the Republic of China runs in the latitudinal direction. The dense forest starts from the height of {{cvt|1200|m}}. Here grow fir, spruce, aspen, birch and poplar. It is here in Dzungaria that the most apple trees in [[Kazakhstan]] remain (49%), including the [[Malus sieversii|Sievers apple]] tree, which is the ancestor of all most domestic apple trees on Earth.\n\nOn the shores of the lake, deciduous groves have grown, which acquire a special beauty in autumn. The area of lake Zhasylkol is an excellent habitat for a large population of marals. Until the eighties of the last century, almost no human set foot here, which is not surprising, because the state border between [[China]] and [[Kazakhstan]] passes here. Traveling here is a great opportunity where virgin nature is evident with its magical views.\n\nThe lake is located in Zhetysu Alatau, {{cvt|23|km}} southwest of the village of [[Lepsinsk]], in the middle reaches of the Kikozen river, one of the sources of the Agynykatty river. From the wheat apiary to the lake along the path winding along the valley of the Agynykatty river \u2013 about {{cvt|10|km}}, from the lake to the Jaeger cordon Zhalanash more than {{cvt|13|km}}.\nThe object is part of the state national nature Park Zhongar-Alatau<ref name=\"sarkan-zhongaralatau-kz\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sarkan-zhongaralatau-kz.online|title=\u041c\u043e\u044f \u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 - www.sarkan-zhongaralatau-kz.online|website=sarkan-zhongaralatau-kz.online|accessdate=2020-03-22}}</ref> and has a favorable acoustic environment (e.g. silence and melodic sounds in nature). The best time to travel is from May to October\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n===Sources===\n*A. A. Akhmatov, A. G. Pozdeyev Guide to the Almaty region. Almaty, 2012\n*[https://bb.kaznu.kz/index.php/biology/article/view/1062 M. Zh. Zhandaev Nature Of The TRANS-Ili Alatau.Almaty, \"Kazakhstan\", 1978]\n\n{{Lakes of Kazakhstan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zhasylkol Lake}}\n[[Category:Lakes of Kazakhstan]]\n", "name_user": "Pratat", "label": "safe", "comment": "removed leadmissing template after lead section was created. removed some double spacing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zhasylkol_Lake"}
{"title_page": "South Brunswick, New Jersey", "text_new": "{{short description|Township in Middlesex County, New Jersey, United States}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = South Brunswick, New Jersey\n|official_name            = Township of South Brunswick\n|settlement_type          = [[Township (New Jersey)|Township]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    = \n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = GULICK HOUSE, MIDDLESEX COUNTY, NJ.jpg\n|imagesize                = 250x200px\n|image_caption            = [[Red Maple Farm]]\n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               = \n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map                = SouthBrunswick-twp-nj.png\n|mapsize                  = 200px\n|map_caption              = Location of South Brunswick within Middlesex County.\n|image_map1               = Census_Bureau_map_of_South_Brunswick_Township,_New_Jersey.png\n|mapsize1                 = 250x200px\n|map_caption1             = Census Bureau map of South Brunswick, New Jersey.\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name         = {{nowrap|{{flag|United States}}}}\n|subdivision_name1        = {{flag|New Jersey}}\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in New Jersey|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Middlesex County, New Jersey|Middlesex]]\n|government_footnotes     = <ref name=DataBook/>\n|government_type          = [[Faulkner Act (Council-Manager)]]\n|governing_body           = Township Council\n|leader_title             = [[Mayor]]\n|leader_name              = Charlie Carley ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]], term ends December 31, 2022)<ref name=Council/><ref>[https://www.state.nj.us/dca/home/2020mayors.pdf 2020 New Jersey Mayors Directory], [[New Jersey Department of Community Affairs]]. Accessed February 1, 2020.</ref>\n