2010>[http://lwd.dol.state.nj.us/labor/lpa/census/2010/dp/dp1_mid/southbrunswick1.pdf Profile of General Demographic Characteristics: 2010 for South Brunswick township] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402032759/http://lwd.dol.state.nj.us/labor/lpa/census/2010/dp/dp1_mid/southbrunswick1.pdf |date=April 2, 2012 }}, [[New Jersey Department of Labor and Workforce Development]]. Accessed September 21, 2012.</ref>\n|population_total         = 43417\n|population_rank          = 43rd of 566 in state<br>8th of 25 in county<ref name=GCTPH1NJ2010>[http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.ST16/0400000US34 GCT-PH1 Population, Housing Units, Area, and Density: 2010 \u2013 State \u2013 County Subdivision from the 2010 Census Summary File 1 for New Jersey] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20200212202329/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.ST16/0400000US34 |date=February 12, 2020 }}, [[United States Census Bureau]]. Accessed September 21, 2012.</ref>\n|population_density_km2   = auto\n|population_density_sq_mi = 1068.1\n|population_density_rank  = 373rd of 566 in state<br>23rd of 25 in county<ref name=GCTPH1NJ2010/>\n|population_est           = 45942\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes        = <ref name=PopEst/>\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset               = \u221205:00\n|timezone_DST             = [[Eastern Daylight Time|Eastern (EDT)]]\n|utc_offset_DST           = \u221204:00\n|elevation_footnotes      = <ref>{{Gnis|882162|Township of South Brunswick}}, [[Geographic Names Information System]]. Accessed September 21, 2012.</ref>\n|elevation_m              = \n|elevation_ft             = 82\n|coordinates_footnotes    = <ref name=CensusArea/><ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=April 23, 2011|date=February 12, 2011|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n|coordinates              = {{coord|40.385022|-74.522936|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP Code]]s\n|postal_code              = 08810 \u2013 [[Dayton, New Jersey|Dayton]]<ref>[http://tools.usps.com/go/ZipLookupResultsAction!input.action?resultMode=0&city=dayton&state=NJ Look Up a ZIP Code for Dayton, NJ], [[United States Postal Service]]. Accessed November 27, 2012.</ref><br>08824 \u2013 [[Kendall Park, New Jersey|Kendall Park]]<ref>[http://tools.usps.com/go/ZipLookupResultsAction!input.action?resultMode=0&city=kendall%20park&state=NJ Look Up a ZIP Code for Kendall Park, NJ], [[United States Postal Service]]. Accessed November 27, 2012.</ref><br>08852 \u2013 [[Monmouth Junction, New Jersey|Monmouth Junction]]<ref>[http://tools.usps.com/go/ZipLookupResultsAction!input.action?resultMode=0&city=monmouth%20junction&state=NJ Look Up a ZIP Code for Monmouth Junction, NJ], [[United States Postal Service]]. Accessed November 27, 2012.</ref><br>08540 \u2013 [[Kingston, New Jersey|Kingston]]<ref>[http://tools.usps.com/go/ZipLookupResultsAction!input.action?resultMode=0&city=kingston&state=NJ Look Up a ZIP Code for Kingston, NJ], [[United States Postal Service]]. Accessed November 27, 2012.</ref><ref name=Thinking/>\n|area_code                = [[Area code 609|609]] and [[Area codes 732 and 848|732]]<ref>[http://www.area-codes.com/search.asp?frmNPA=&frmNXX=&frmState=NJ&frmCity=South%20Brunswick&frmCounty=Middlesex Area Code Lookup \u2013 NPA NXX for South Brunswick, NJ], Area-Codes.com. Accessed September 24, 2014.</ref>\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standards|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 3402368790<ref name=CensusArea/><ref name=\"GR2\">[https://www.census.gov U.S. Census website] , [[United States Census Bureau]]. Accessed September 4, 2014.</ref><ref>[https://census.missouri.edu/geocodes/?state=34 Geographic codes for New Jersey], Missouri Census Data Center. Accessed September 1, 2019.</ref>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0882162<ref name=CensusArea/><ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=October 25, 2007}}</ref>\n|website                  = {{URL|https://www.southbrunswicknj.gov/}}\n|footnotes                = \n}}\n'''South Brunswick''' is a [[Township (New Jersey)|township]] in [[Middlesex County, New Jersey|Middlesex County]], [[New Jersey]], United States.  As of the [[2010 United States Census]], the township's population was 43,417,<ref name=Census2010/><ref name=Districts2011/><ref name=LWD2010/> reflecting an increase of 5,683 (+15.1%) from the 37,734 counted in the [[2000 United States Census|2000 Census]], which had in turn increased by 11,942 (+46.3%) from the 25,792 counted in the [[1990 United States Census|1990 Census]].<ref>[http://lwd.dol.state.nj.us/labor/lpa/census/2010/2010data/table7cm.xls Table 7. Population for the Counties and Municipalities in New Jersey: 1990, 2000 and 2010] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807100630/http://lwd.dol.state.nj.us/labor/lpa/census/2010/2010data/table7cm.xls |date=August 7, 2017 }}, [[New Jersey Department of Labor and Workforce Development]], February 2011. Accessed September 21, 2012.</ref>\n\nSouth Brunswick was first mentioned in Freeholder minutes on February 28, 1778, as being formed from [[New Brunswick, New Jersey|New Brunswick Township]]. It was formally incorporated as one of New Jersey's initial group of 104 townships on February 21, 1798. Portions of the township have been taken to form [[Cranbury, New Jersey|Cranbury Township]] (as of March 7, 1872) and [[Plainsboro Township, New Jersey|Plainsboro Township]] (on April 1, 1919).<ref name=Story>Snyder, John P. [https://www.state.nj.us/dep/njgs/enviroed/oldpubs/bulletin67.pdf ''The Story of New Jersey's Civil Boundaries: 1606\u20131968''], Bureau of Geology and Topography; Trenton, New Jersey; 1969. p. 174. Accessed September 21, 2012.</ref>\n\n[[CNNMoney.com]] ranked South Brunswick Township 22nd on its 2011 list of the \"Best Places to Live\", featuring its picks of the best small towns in the United States.<ref>Staff. [http://money.cnn.com/magazines/moneymag/bplive/2011/snapshots/CS3468790.html \"2011 Best Places to Live: 22. South Brunswick, NJ\"], [[CNNMoney.com]], from ''[[Money (magazine)|Money]]'', September 2011. Accessed August 18, 2011.</ref>\n\nIn 2016, SafeWise named South Brunswick Township as the tenth-safest city in America to raise a child; the township was the third-highest ranked of the 12 communities in New Jersey included on the list.<ref>Maurer, Caroline. [http://www.safewise.com/blog/safest-cities-to-raise-a-child/ \"The 30 Safest Cities to Raise a Child \u2013 2016\"], SafeWise, June 27, 2016. Accessed August 22, 2016.</ref>\n\n==History==\nSouth Brunswick Township was incorporated by an act of the [[New Jersey Legislature]] on February 21, 1798.<ref name=Story/> In the 18th and 19th centuries, the community was primarily agricultural. The Straight Turnpike, now [[U.S. Route 1 in New Jersey|U.S. Route 1]], was constructed in 1804.<ref name=History>[https://www.southbrunswicknj.gov/community/history History], Township of South Brunswick. Accessed March 8, 2020.</ref> The township got its name from New Brunswick, which in turn was named after the city of [[Braunschweig]] (called ''Brunswick'' in the [[Low German]] language), in state of [[Lower Saxony]], in [[Germany]]. Braunschweig was an influential and powerful city in the [[Hanseatic League]], later in the [[Holy Roman Empire]], and was an administrative seat for the Duchy (and later Principality) of Hanover. Shortly after the first settlement of New Brunswick in colonial New Jersey, George, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg, and Elector of Hanover, of the [[House of Hanover]] (also known as the ''House of Brunswick''), became [[George I of Great Britain|King George I of Great Britain]] (1660\u20131727). Alternatively, the city derived its name from King [[George II of Great Britain]], the [[Duchy of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg]].<ref>Hutchinson, Viola L. [http://mapmaker.rutgers.edu/356/nj_place_names_origin.pdf#page=23 ''The Origin of New Jersey Place Names''], New Jersey Public Library Commission, May 1945. Accessed October 7, 2015.</ref><ref>[[Henry Gannett|Gannett, Henry]]. [https://books.google.com/books?id=9V1IAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA223 ''The Origin of Certain Place Names in the United States''], p. 223. [[United States Government Printing Office]], 1905. Accessed October 7, 2015.</ref>\n\nIn 1872, the Legislature first reduced the size of South Brunswick with the creation of the separate [[Cranbury, New Jersey|Cranbury Township]] from the southern portion of South Brunswick. In 1885, it redefined and enlarged the boundaries of Cranbury, and [[Plainsboro Township, New Jersey|Plainsboro Township]] was formed in 1919. The present boundaries of South Brunswick date back to this last change.<ref name=Story/>\n\nDuring the 20th century, South Brunswick saw extensive transformation with the impact of changes in transportation technology. The [[New Brunswick and Trenton Fast Line]] began operation in 1900, a trolley line running parallel to the Old Straight Turnpike of 1804 ([[U.S. Route 1 in New Jersey|Route 1]]), intersecting George's Road just north of the Five Corners intersection in Dayton. This trolley provided daily passenger and freight service, stopping at a local crossroads. The [[New Jersey Turnpike]] opened in 1951, again roughly parallel to Route 1, on the eastern edge of the Township. One effect of the Turnpike opening up Interchange 8A (just outside the township) was the transformation of the agricultural area on the southeast corner of South Brunswick to that of a burgeoning industrial development. Significant portions of land between Route 130 and the [[New Jersey Turnpike|turnpike]] consist largely of warehouses.<ref>Cifelli, Melissa. [http://ns.gmnews.com/news/2005-07-28/Front_page/001.html \" A landscape changes from silos to storage; Over 5M square feet of warehouses proposed in eastern S.B. this year\"]{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''Sentinel'', July 28, 2005. Accessed October 7, 2015.</ref>\n\nIn 1980, the township's population approached 18,000. In 1990, this figure reached 25,792 and by 2010, South Brunswick had over 43,000 residents. Much of the township's {{convert|42|sqmi|km2}} remain undeveloped and there are still significant amounts of wetlands, woodlands and open space within the community.\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the township had a total area of 41.039 square miles (106.290&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>), including 40.648 square miles (105.278&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>) of land and 0.391 square miles (1.012&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>) of water (0.95%).<ref name=CensusArea/><ref name=\"GR1\" />\n\n[[Dayton, New Jersey|Dayton]] (2010 Census population of 7,063<ref>[http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/1600000US3416630 DP-1 \u2013 Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Demographic Profile Data for Dayton CDP, New Jersey] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20200212144017/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/1600000US3416630 |date=February 12, 2020 }}, [[United States Census Bureau]]. Accessed September 20, 2012.</ref>), [[Heathcote, New Jersey|Heathcote]] (5,821<ref>[http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/1600000US3430738 DP-1 \u2013 Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Demographic Profile Data for Heathcote CDP, New Jersey] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20200212162748/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/1600000US3430738 |date=February 12, 2020 }}, [[United States Census Bureau]]. Accessed September 20, 2012.</ref>), [[Kendall Park, New Jersey|Kendall Park]] (9,339<ref>[http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/1600000US3436660 DP-1 \u2013 Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Demographic Profile Data for Kendall Park CDP, New Jersey] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20200212133442/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/1600000US3436660 |date=February 12, 2020 }}, [[United States Census Bureau]]. Accessed September 20, 2012.</ref>), [[Kingston, New Jersey|Kingston]] (1,222 of a total CDP population of 1,493, with the balance in [[Franklin Township, Somerset County, New Jersey|Franklin Township]]<ref>[http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/1600000US3436930 DP-1 \u2013 Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Demographic Profile Data for Kingston CDP, New Jersey] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20200212143322/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/1600000US3436930 |date=February 12, 2020 }}, [[United States Census Bureau]]. Accessed September 20, 2012.</ref>) and [[Monmouth Junction, New Jersey|Monmouth Junction]] (2,887<ref>[http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/1600000US3447190 DP-1 \u2013 Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Demographic Profile Data for Monmouth Junction CDP, New Jersey] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20200212132949/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/1600000US3447190 |date=February 12, 2020 }}, [[United States Census Bureau]]. Accessed September 20, 2012.</ref>) are [[Local government in New Jersey#Unincorporated communities|unincorporated communities]] and [[census-designated place]]s (CDPs) located within South Brunswick Township.<ref>[https://www.census.gov/prod/cen2010/cph-2-32.pdf New Jersey: 2010 \u2013 Population and Housing Unit Counts \u2013 2010 Census of Population and Housing (CPH-2-32)], [[United States Census Bureau]], August 2012. Accessed November 27, 2012.</ref><ref>[http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US34023 GCT-PH1 \u2013 Population, Housing Units, Area, and Density: 2010 \u2013 County \u2013 County Subdivision and Place from the 2010 Census Summary File 1 for Middlesex County, New Jersey] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20200212200723/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US34023 |date=February 12, 2020 }}, [[United States Census Bureau]]. Accessed November 27, 2012.</ref>\n\nOther unincorporated communities, localities and place names located partially or completely within the township include:<ref>[http://www.state.nj.us/infobank/localnames.txt Locality Search], State of [[New Jersey]]. Accessed April 15, 2015.</ref> [[Cottageville, New Jersey|Cottageville]],{{citation needed|date=April 2015}} [[Deans, New Jersey|Deans]], [[Franklin Park, Middlesex County, New Jersey|Franklin Park]], [[Fresh Ponds, New Jersey|Fresh Ponds]], [[Little Rocky Hill, New Jersey|Little Rocky Hill]], [[Sand Hills, South Brunswick, New Jersey|Sand Hills]], [[South Brunswick Terrace, New Jersey|South Brunswick Terrace]]{{citation needed|date=April 2015}} and Ten Mile Run.\n\nBecause the township is served by several different zip codes, Dayton, Monmouth Junction, Kendall Park, Kingston, Jamesburg, Cranbury, Princeton and even North Brunswick are often used in place of the township's name, even when referring to areas located beyond their defined boundaries.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nDayton was first known simply as The Cross Roads, where James Whitlock built a tavern on Georges Road around 1750. Early enterprises included a brick manufacturer and large nursery. In 1866, the name was changed from Cross Roads to Dayton, in honor of [[William L. Dayton]], an attorney for the Freehold and Jamesburg Agricultural Railroad. Dayton had helped settle disputes arising from the location of a railroad right-of-way. He was later a [[United States Senate|United States Senator]], was the first [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for Vice President (in 1856), and Minister to France.<ref name=Birth>Chang, Kathy; and Kesten, Karen L. [https://archive.centraljersey.com/2009/12/17/birth-of-a-town-10/ \"Birth of a town\"], ''South Brunswick Sentinel'', June 2, 2011. Accessed March 8, 2020.</ref>\n\nDeans originated from its location on both Crosswicknung Trail (Georges Road) and Lawrence Brook. Dams were built on the brook, creating Deans Pond.<ref name=Birth/>\n\nWith increased mobility and a growing population, the suburban-style residential development was born after [[World War II]], and Kendall Park was begun in the 1950s. Kendall Park is located off [[New Jersey Route 27|Route 27]], the old Indian trail and major thoroughfare of earlier centuries.\n\nKingston's location on the [[Lenape]] [[Assunpink Trail]] where it crossed the [[Millstone River]] was the prime factor in its early prominence. Kingston was by far the most active and important community, being situated on both the heavily traveled King's Road and Millstone River, combining commercial activities of both mills and taverns. The [[Kingston Village Advisory Committee]], jointly appointed by the South Brunswick and [[Franklin Township, Somerset County, New Jersey|Franklin Township]] Councils, reports to the Township Council on matters of concern to residents of [[Kingston, New Jersey|Kingston]].<ref>[http://www.villageofkingston.com/Website/advisory.html Kingston Village Advisory Committee] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929151505/http://www.villageofkingston.com/Website/advisory.html |date=September 29, 2007 }}, Village of Kingston. Accessed September 6, 2007.</ref> Kingston has been designated as a [[Village Center]] by the [[New Jersey State Planning Commission]] and is overseen by an advisory commission that consists of seven members from Franklin Township and South Brunswick.<ref>[https://www.southbrunswicknj.gov/kingston-village Kingston Village Advisory Committee], Township of South Brunswick. Accessed March 8, 2020. \"The KVAC is a committee of seven members from South Brunswick and Franklin Townships.  KVAC oversees the implementation of the Planning and Implementation Agenda which was approved by the New Jersey State Planning Commission when Kingston was designated as a Village Center.\"</ref>\n\nMonmouth Junction was created as the junction of three rail branches, the New York division of the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]], the Rocky Hill and the Jamesburg and Freehold.<ref name=Birth/>\n\nThe [[Lawrence Brook]], a tributary of the [[Raritan River]], flows through the township.\n\n[[Pigeon Swamp State Park]] is a [[List of New Jersey state parks|New Jersey state park]] located on Deans Rhode Hall Road ([[County Route 610 (Middlesex County, New Jersey)|Middlesex CR-610]]). The park has {{convert|1078|acre|km2}} of undeveloped land.<ref>[http://nynjctbotany.org/njiptofc/pigeon.html Pigeon Swamp State Park], [[New York\u2013New Jersey Trail Conference]]. Accessed July 13, 2016.</ref> \n\nThe [https://centraljersey.com/2017/10/10/the-2018-calendar-to-highlight-historical-moments-in-south-brunswick-3/ Pigeon Swamp Ledger] is a 1780 document that is an accounting log of South Brunswick land owners regarding the draining of the Pigeon Swamp.  This was made possible by an [https://play.google.com/books/reader?id=dCVIAQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&pg=GBS.PA133 New Jersey Act of Legislature].\n\nThe township borders [[Cranbury, New Jersey|Cranbury Township]], [[East Brunswick, New Jersey|East Brunswick Township]], [[Monroe Township, Middlesex County, New Jersey|Monroe Township]], [[North Brunswick, New Jersey|North Brunswick Township]] and [[Plainsboro Township, New Jersey|Plainsboro Township]] in Middlesex County; [[Princeton, New Jersey|Princeton]] in [[Mercer County, New Jersey|Mercer County]]; and [[Franklin Township, Somerset County, New Jersey|Franklin Township]] in [[Somerset County, New Jersey|Somerset County]].<ref>[https://global.mapit.mysociety.org/area/1085055/touches.html Areas touching South Brunswick], MapIt. Accessed March 8, 2020.</ref><ref>[http://www.middlesexcountynj.gov/Government/Pages/Municipalities.aspx Municipalities], [[Middlesex County, New Jersey]]. Accessed December 1, 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.state.nj.us/transportation/gis/maps/polnoroads.pdf New Jersey Municipal Boundaries], [[New Jersey Department of Transportation]]. Accessed November 15, 2019.</ref>\n\n===Climate===\nSouth Brunswick is in the [[humid continental climate]] zone. Average Winter-time high temperatures range from {{convert|38|to|43|F|C}}, and the lows range from {{convert|19|to|24|F|C}} degrees with the record low being {{convert|-16|F|C}}. Average summer-time high temperatures range from {{convert|84|to|87|F|C}}, though temperatures exceed {{convert|90|F|C}} often with the record high being {{convert|105|F|C}}. The summertime lows range from {{convert|63|to|67|F|C}} degrees. South Brunswick can receive much snow during the winter months, sometimes up to {{convert|3|ft}}. About {{convert|4|to|5|in|cm}} of rain falls every month, and is evenly spread throughout the year, though the area can go through long periods of drought or long-lasting periods with little to no rain. During winter and early spring, South Brunswick can in some years experience \"[[nor'easter]]s\", which are capable of causing blizzards or flooding throughout the northeastern United States. Hurricanes and tropical storms (such as [[Hurricane Irene]] in 2011), tornadoes and earthquakes are rare.\n\n{{Weather box |metric first =\n|location = South Brunswick Township (Dayton), New Jersey\n|single line = y\n|Jan high F = 39\n|Feb high F = 43\n|Mar high F = 51\n|A